Commentary.Commentary: We are back for West Indies' reply! The English players have made their way out to the middle. Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell to open the batting for West Indies. Chris Woakes will start proceedings with the ball for England. Three slips and a gully in place. Here we go...
... Second innings ...

West Indies had a sensational start as their bowlers were breathing fire with the red cherry. Kemar Roach, Jayden Seales wrecked England's top order and Jason Holder followed it up by  bowling impeccable lines and lengths and with great consistency and also bagged the wicket of Lawrence. It was a different story later as in the middle and the final session, as they allowed some partnerships to build and were blown away by Bairstow's counter-attack. It was the short ball ploy that worked in their favor on Day 2, as Seales struck twice and then Joseph ended the proceedings bagging two wickets. They would be pleased that they didn't allow England to add much to their overnight score and now it's onto their batters to come out and show positive intent. Their first target would be to enter the Lunch unscathed. Let's see if they are able to achieve that or not.

Electing to bat first, England were in all sorts of trouble as the top order collapsed leaving the side with 48/4. After that, Stokes and Foakes stitched crucial partnerships with Bairstow but they could not convert their starts. However, Jonny Bairstow bailed England out of trouble with a remarkable century and they ended Day 1 on 268/6. He found another sustainable partner in Chris Woakes and they built a 71-run stand before Woakes holed out. The tail-enders could not do much with the bat and England added 43 runs to their overnight score with Bairstow walking back with just 10 runs short of his 150 . If it hadn't been him, England would have never reached here. All the credit to Bairstow for putting up a show and helping England to get out of the rut.
Jonny Bairstow walks back with a huge round of applause from the English supporters and his teammates. A fine innings from him as it has lifted England to 311.

Commentary.Howout: c Jason Holder b Alzarri Joseph

We are set for Day 2 to get underway! The players have made their way out to the middle. The overnight batters, Chris Woakes and Jonny Bairstow are at the crease. Kemar Roach will start proceedings with the ball. Here we go...

PITCH REPORT - Mark Butcher is near the pitch. He says that the breeze is up, and it's expected to be another hot day. Reckons that the surface is holding together okay for now, but there's every chance it is going to start crumbling sooner rather than later. Adds that they can get increasing variable bounce as the game progresses.

Jayden Seales is up for a quick chat as well. He says, he tried to bowl full and in good areas but he could have been more consistent. Tells that the pitch is a bit on the slower side and hence bowling full was very important. Mentions that he enjoyed bowling from the Andy Roberts end.

Ben Foakes is up for a chat. He says that Jonny batted really well and he tried to be disciplined with the bat. Tells that there is enough in the wicket for the bowlers and anything around 350 would be a good score on this pitch.

Jonny Bairstow was the talk of the town on Day 1 as England had slipped to 48/4 in the first session but they finished Day 1 with 268/6 and it was led by a hundred from the Englishman. With him still at the crease, England would at least be eyeing 350, while the hosts would look to minimize the damage. They were terrific with the new ball on Day 1 and would be hoping for a similar performance. Let's see what Day 2 has in store for us.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 2 of the first Test between England and West Indies. We witnessed an entertaining Day 1 with England ending the day in a commanding position. The hosts have however fared well and are not out of this contest. While England would be looking to add as many runs as they can, the hosts would look to make early inroads as the ball is still relatively new and they would hope to wrap things up quickly and come out to bat. Another thrilling session awaits us.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

Right then. Jonny Bairstow played a valiant knock to put his side in a commanding position. He has gotten England out of the woods. England would love to see him bat for as long as he could on Day 2. West Indies, on the other side, seem to have lost a trick with the ball after a dominating morning session. But the ball is still fairly new and the hosts would hope to start the morning session on Day 2 in a similar fashion. The first ball will be bowled at 1930 IST (1400 GMT). Do join us then. Till then, take care and goodbye!

Jonny Bairstow is in for a quick chat. He says, that scoring a ton feels amazing and it is great fun playing here. Tells that they spoke about partnerships and how crucial they could be. Mentions that there is still plenty on the pitch and they will have to see how it goes in the morning session. Adds that they will try to add as many runs as possible.

Kemar Roach is in for a chat. He says that the pitch played a lot better than what they expected. Tells that they started well in the Lunch session and got on the back foot after that but are still happy. Mentions that his plan for tomorrow is to get early wickets and be more consistent with his lines and lengths.

The bowlers lost control as the ball became old. Unlike the first session, the pacers were unable to threat the batters with any kind of movement. This forced Kraigg Brathwaite to get his spinner into the attack. But it did not work in their favour, as Bairstow and Foakes dealt with ease and kept racking up runs at a brisk rate. West Indies looked down and under, as the sixth-wicket stand kept growing. It was Jason Holder who came out with a moment of inspiration and got the better of Foakes. The hosts would’ve loved to capitalize on this opening but were not able to cause any more damage. The bowlers failed to keep tight lines and lengths in the final session.

What a session for England this was. They lost only a single wicket of Ben Foakes, that too after he put up a solid stand of 99 runs with Jonny Bairstow while England racked up 123 runs in the final session. Well, Bairstow who was kept in the side for racking up runs down the order, seems to have accepted the role with open arms as he racked up his eighth Test century. If not for him, England would’ve been bundled out for a cheaper score. Chris Woakes showed good resilience in the end and made sure to remain unscathed till Stumps. The knock by the middle order really tells you that there is nothing wrong with the wicket or the batting conditions. The top-order batters of England really need to step up.

What a comeback by the visitors! They were bogged down to 57/4 at the end of the first session. But England did really well to recover in the next two sessions. It was Jonny Bairstow, who was the backbone of this English innings. In the final hour of the final session, Bairstow-Woakes stitched a solid stand of 54 runs to end their day on a high. Jonny Bairstow walks back with a huge round of applause from his team-mates and he deserves every bit of this.

Drinks! Just when the partnership between Foakes and Bairstow was threatening to take the game away from Windies, Holder has provided the breakthrough. However, England have done well to get back into this game with Bairstow playing a valiant knock and Foakes giving him a good company. Jayden Seales is in for a quick chat. He says that he was riding on the danger area and he has to work on it. Mentions, earlier in the morning he found it a bit difficult to find his rhythm. On being asked about the wicket of Stokes, he says, it was supposed to be his last over and only aimed to bowl his best. Adds they would like to restrict England to a low score and not let them get to comfort zone.

Session Summary - 27 overs, 88 runs, 1 wicket. After reeling at 48-4, Jonny Bairstow and Ben Stokes did well to steady the ship for England. Both played positive cricket post Lunch. Their partnership slowly started to restore the balance and also scored at a very good pace. But just when the partnership was blossoming, Seales bowled a ripper to get rid of Stokes. Since then, Foakes has started off on a good note and he and Bairstow made sure to head into the Tea break without any further hiccups. West Indies will enjoy this break and would be very happy about their performance till now. They have bowled exceedingly well maintaining tight lines and lengths and always kept the pressure on the opponents. The result? They got 5 wickets in total and will now look to end England's innings in the final session. Do join us at 12.30 am IST ( 7 pm GMT, previous day) for that.

Length ball, on off. Bairstow blocks it back to the bowler.
BEATEN! A full-length ball, outside off. It nips away a shade. Jonny Bairstow tries to reach out but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Short ball, outside off. Jonny Bairstow steps across and shoulders his arms at it.
Back of a length, on middle and leg. Ben Stokes pulls it to deep square leg for a single.
Fuller, wide outside off, Stokes has no stroke to offer.
A length ball, outside off. Ben Stokes leaves it alone.

FOUR! Jonny Bairstow would be the happiest man to see it race away to the boundary line. It is a short delivery, on off. Jonny Bairstow tries to pull it away but is a tad early into his shot. The ball flies off the top-edge and evades the effort of two fielders from the slip chasing it towards third man. It lands safely and gets into the fence.
Length ball, outside off. Jonny Bairstow pushes it through backward point for a brace.
Another one outside off, Jonny Bairstow leaves it alone yet again.
Slightly short, outside off, moving away. Jonny Bairstow lets it go to the keeper.
Good length, outside off, shaping away. Jonny Bairstow leaves it alone for the keeper.
Full length, on the pads. Ben Stokes clips it through mid-wicket. The batters take three before the fielder cuts it out.
Length ball, on the fourth stump line. Jonny Bairstow shoulders his arms at it.
Back of a length, on the body. Jonny Bairstow tries to heave it across the line but misses.
Full length, on off. Stokes pushes it to cover for a single.
FOUR! Ben Stokes freeing his arms now. A length ball, outside off. Some extra bounce off the deck. Ben Stokes gets on top of the bounce and punches it through covers for a boundary.
A length ball, on middle and leg. Stokes blocks it out watchfully.
A length ball, on middle and leg. It flies off the deck. Ben Stokes tries to flick it away but misses and gets hit high on the pads.
On a length, outside off. Left alone by Bairstow.
Pushed much wider, outside off. Bairstow with an another leave.
Better from Seales! Length ball, outside off, shaping away. Bairstow lets it sail through.
FOUR! Absoultely smashed! Short of a length, on off. Jonny Bairstow slaps it away in front of the square. The ball races away to the vacant deep mid-wicket fence in a jiffy.
Good-length ball, outside off. Jonny Bairstow shoulders arms to that.
Length ball, pushed well outside off. Jonny Bairstow is not chasing that one.

We are back for the second session. The players walk out to the middle. Followed by Ben Stokes and Jonny Bairstow who walk out with their swords for England. Jayden Seales to start with the ball post Lunch.
... Day 1, Session 2 ...

Right then. England batters have their task cut out after an horrendous display with the blade. West Indies, on the flip side, have the upper hand in the game. They will hope to come back in the second session and try to wrap things up as early as possible. An enticing session of cricket awaits. Do join us at 2210 IST (1640 GMT) for the middle session to find out what happens.

A four-men pace attack is certainly doing the trick for West Indies. The first session certainly belonged to them as they gave away only 57 runs and took 4 wickets. The opening bowling pair of Roach-Seales made sure to keep things tight and put the visitors on the back foot instantly. Roach bagged two wickets while Seales took a wicket. But to be honest, Jason Holder was pick of the bowlers in the morning session, as he bowled 5 maiden overs on the trot and also got a wicket under his belly.

The opening woes continue for England in Test cricket. The English camp added some new names to the side while shockingly left out some big names, and thought this may turn things around for them. But it certainly did not go as per their plan. England openers were sent back to the pavilion within the opening 4 overs, but Zak Crawley and Alex Lees did hit some glorious shots before folding out. The visitors even lost Root soon after and Dan Lawrence followed suit. But in the end, Stokes and Bairstow made sure to remain unscathed till Lunch on Day 1.

Oh my god! What cricket did we just witness? Looks like the hosts have blown away the opposition in the first session itself. The English batters could not justify their skipper’s decision to bat first and see themselves teetering at 57/4. It is harsh but it’s the truth that England’s poor form with the bat in red-ball cricket prevails.
A single to end the over! On a good length, on middle. Jonny Bairstow hops and clips it to square leg for a single. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 1!
Length ball, attacking the stumps. Jonny Bairstow works it to mid-wicket.
Length ball, on off. Jonny Bairstow is solid in his defence.
On a good length, on off, shaping away a tad. Jonny Bairstow with a good watchful leave.
Touch fuller, outside off, shaping away. Jonny Bairstow decides not to offer any shot.
Outside off, on a length. Bairstow lets it be.
Full and nipping away, outside off. Stokes shoulders arms.
Comes round the wicket to Stokes and bowls a length ball, outside off. Stokes lets it through.
Full and slanting in, on middle. Bairstow flicks it through mid on. Roach gives it a chase and keeps it down to a single.
On a good length, on off. Bairstow blocks it out.
Lovely shot! Shorter and wider, outside off. Bairstow punches it through cover-point for a brace.
Length ball, outside off. Bairstow leaves it alone.
Touch fuller, outside off. Stokes crunches his drive straight to extra cover.
First runs after 19 deliveries! On the pads, Stokes flicks it through mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Stokes with another watchful leave.
Length ball, outside off. Stokes lets it be.
A full toss, outside off. Stokes is surprised by that and he fails to put it away. Hits it off the inner half of the bat back to the bowler.
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Stokes is not interested to offer a shot.
Length ball, on off. Bairstow covers the line and pushes it to the on side.
Outside off, on a length. Bairstow blocks it to the off side.
Good-length ball, on off. Bairstow keeps it out this time to the off side.
An action replay of the previous delivery! Bairstow lets it sail through.
Jonny Bairstow shoulders amrs to this length ball which is bowled outside off.
Length ball, outside off, shaping away. Jonny Bairstow leaves it for the keeper to collect.
Kemar Roach (6-1-28-2) comes back into the attack.
Good length, outside off. Ben Stokes defends it to the off side. Fifth maiden on the trot for Jason Holder.
Overpitched, outside off. Ben Stokes leaves it alone for the keeper.
Length, outside off, moving away. Ben Stokes has no stroke to offer.
Fuller. wide outside off. Stokes leaves it alone.
A length ball, at 124 kph, on off. It flies off the deck. Ben Stokes is surprised as he blocks it out awkwardly.
A full-length ball, on off. Ben Stokes gets an inside edge on the pads.
Length ball, outside off, shaping in late. Jonny Bairstow trusts the bounces and shoulders his arms at it.
Good-length ball, outside off, with some extra bounce. Jonny Bairstow does not go chasing.
Length ball, on off. Jonny Bairstow blocks it back to the bowler.
A length ball, around off. Stokes pushes it to cover for one.
Full and slanting away, outside off. Stokes offers no shot.
Length, angling away, outside off. Stokes lets it go.
Nice little outswinger by Holder, on off. Bairstow counters it nicely as well. Fourth consecutive maidens for Holder!
On a length, outside off. Bairstow with yet another leave.
Fuller in length, on off. Bairstow pushes it to mid on.
Outside off, Bairstow defends it out.
Well bowled! On a good length, around off, nipping away. Jonny Bairstow watches the seam closely and decides to leave.
Length ball, outside off, shaping away. Jonny Bairstow leaves it for the keeper to collect.
Drop and run! Short of a length, on off. Jonny Bairstow stands tall and drops it to the off side and scampers through. 50 comes up for England!
Length ball, outside off. Bairstow lets it sail through.
Back of a length, outside off. Stokes hops and works it to the off side for a run.
Nice and full, on off. Stokes defends it out.
Full and on leg, Ben Stokes misses his flick and gets hit on the pads. A muted appeal for an lbw but not given.
Length ball, outside off, coming in. The ball shoots up after pitching. Ben Stokes lets it go.
On a good length, outside off. Jonny Bairstow shoulders arms. Another successful over for Jason Holder. A wicket-maiden this time!
Length ball, straightens up after pitching around off. Jonny Bairstow blocks it out off the front foot.
There is some halt in play. Looks like the DJ is having some issue with his set up. There is some disturbance cause due to the same. Looks like we are good to continue.
Jonny Bairstow is the new man in.

OUT! TAKEN! Jason Holder gets his reward for persisting with good line and lengths. He didn't give anything away in his first two overs and finally, gets a scalp. Bowls a good-length ball, on middle and off and shapes it away. Dan Lawrence had no choice but to play. He does so but the ball takes the outside edge and flies to second slip. A big relief for Jermaine Blackwood as well as he missed out on a couple of opportunities off Kemar Roach early on but held onto this one moving to his right. Another bites the dust for England! West Indies right on top!
Commentary.Howout: c Jermaine Blackwood b Jason Holder

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, outside off. Left alone.
Length ball, shaping away from off. Dan Lawrence shoulders arms.
On a good length, on middle. Dan Lawrence defends it solidly.
On a length, on off, Stokes solidly blocks it out.
Length ball, outside off, nips away a touch. Stokes leaves it alone for the keeper.
Outside off, left alone.

Dan Lawrence wanted a single but Ben Stokes was not sure about the position of the ball and hence denied the run.
Length ball, on the pads. Dan Lawrence flicks it to mid-wicket for a single.
Length ball, outside off. It flies off the deck. Joshua Da Silva gathers the ball a bit too high.

Second consecutive maiden for Jason Holder. A length ball, outside off, shaping away from the left-hander. Ben Stokes walks out of his crease and tries to push it inside the line but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Length ball, on the pads. Stokes stays inside the crease and tucks it to mid-wicket.
Full length, on off. Stokes defends it back to the bowler with soft hands.
Length ball, on middle and leg. Ben Stokes works it towards mid on.
Fuller, on leg. Stokes defends it to the leg side.
CLOSE! Overpitched, outside off, moving away. Ben Stokes leans in and tries to defend it out. He misses and the ball zips past the outside edge.
Fuller, on the pads, Stokes clips it to the left of short mid-wicket. Kraigg Brathwaite was quick to retain the ball and the batters could only take a single.
Good length, on off, shaping across the left-hander. Ben Stokes stays inside the crease and leaves it alone for the keeper.
Full length, on middle and leg. Dan Lawrence flicks it off his pads towards deep mid-wicket. They take three before the fielder cuts it out.
A short ball, outside off. Dan Lawrence leaves it alone.
Back of a length, on off. Dan Lawrence ducks under it with ease.

FOUR! Nicely played! A length ball, outside off. It nips away a shade with some extra bounce off the deck. Dan Lawrence shuffles across and guides it through backward point with soft hands for a boundary.

Drinks! What a great first hour for West Indies. They have got 3 wickets including the wicket of Joe Root who is the backbone of England. Ben Stokes and Dan Lawrence need to do some repair work now and would look to stay at the crease till Lunch as England cannot afford to lose any more wickets.  Change from both ends! Alzarri Joseph to operate now. He replaces Kemar Roach.
WOAH! A full-length ball, outside off, shaping across Ben Stokes, who tries to go for the booming drive only to get beaten on the outside edge.
Could not find the gap! A full-length ball, outside off, shaping across the left-hander/ Ben Stokes' eye lit up with the width on offer but he only punches it towards short extra cover.
Full length, on off stump. Ben Stokes defends it back to the bowler off the bottom half of the blade.
Fuller, on off. Stokes pushes it out.
A short ball, nipping away, outside off. Ben Stokes shoulders his arms at it.
A full-length ball, at 126 kph, Ben Stokes defends it into the deck.
Jason Holder is brought into the attack now. He replaces Jayden Seales.
Length ball, on off. Dan Lawrence defends it out watchfully.

FOUR! Did it carry though? Streaky boundary for Dan Lawrence. A full-length ball, around off, nips away a touch. Dan Lawrence leans in to defend it out but only finds the outside edge. It goes towards Jermaine Blackwood at third slip but does not carry. Blackwood gets low to his left but is unable to stop the ball as well. It races away to the third man.
A short ball, shaping in late. Dan Lawrence trusts the bounce and shoulders his arms at it. Although the umpire signals a no ball, as the bowler oversteps.
Three dots on the trot! Short and outside off. Dan Lawrence leaves it alone.
Good length, outside off, yet again. Lawrence shoulders his arms at it.
Length ball, on the fifth stump line. Dan Lawrence leaves it alone for the keeper.
FOUR! Easy pickings! Kemar Roach bowls a loose delivery, full and angling down leg. Dan Lawrence stays back and clips it away for a boundary quite comfortably through the square leg region.
A good bouncer! Short ball, on middle. Ben Stokes does well to get away from the line and let it go.
Another beautiful inswinger, on off. Stokes shows his full face of the bat and drives it back to the bowler.
Seales with an inswinger this time, on middle. Lawrence plays it through mid-wicket and gets three runs.
Seales shapes away this length ball, outside off. Dan Lawrence with another leave.
On a good length, outside off. Dan Lawrence shoulders arms.
Lovely outswinger, outside off. Dan Lawrence lets it be.
On a good length, outside off, shaping away. Ben Stokes makes a watchful leave.
On a length, wide outside off, moving away. Ben Stokes walks across the stumps but does not offer any shot.
Back of a length, outside off, shaping away. Ben Stokes leaves it alone for the keeper.
Good-length ball, on off. Ben Stokes blocks it out.
Ben Stokes is the new man in.

OUT! TIMBER! Kemar Roach wins the battle against Joe Root. England in a spot of bother now as their skipper departs for just 13. This is some start from West Indies. Kemar Roach steams in and bowls a good-length ball, at 133 kph, and angles this one in. Joe Root makes an error of judgement as he decides to leave this one and he shoulders arms. This allows the ball to clip the top of the off stump and Kemar Roach is off to a celebration and so are his team-mates as they gather around him.
Commentary.Howout: b Kemar Roach

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! That goes through the third slip! Short of a length, outside off, extra bounce on that one. Joe Root cuts it towards the slip cordon. The ball goes through the hands of the third slip fielder and races away to the fence.

Jayden Seales finally gets one to come back in. An inswinger, outside off, on a good length. Dan Lawrence is taken aback by that and he tries to defend with a full face of the bat. He misses and the ball whizzes past the outside edge.
Outside off, on a length. Dan Lawrence lets it sail through.
Another outswinger which is bowled well outside off, Dan Lawrence is not interested in playing those.
Length ball, outside off, shaping away. Dan Lawrence shoulders his arms.
On a good length, on off, shaping away a tad. Dan Lawrence gets on top of the bounce and defends it out.
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Dan Lawrence with yet another leave.
FOUR! That is nicely played! Full and straight, on middle. Joe Root flicks it through mid-wicket. The timing was exquisite and he gets a boundary for that.
Back of a length, on off. Dan Lawrence pushes it through the cover region for a single.
Pushed wider this time, outside off. Dan Lawrence continues with his leaving spree to anything that is outside off.
On a good length, nipping in, on off. Dan Lawrence blocks it out on the front foot.
Length ball, outside off. Dan Lawrence watches the ball closely and lets it for the keeper to collect.
A quick single! Length ball, straight and on middle, Root covers the line and tucks it to short mid-wicket for a quick single.
Good-length ball, on off, no swing movement this time. Dan Lawrence taps it to point from his crease. Another maiden for Jayden Seales!
Length ball, in the sixth stump channel, Dan Lawrence offers no shot to that one.
On a length, outside off, swinging away. Dan Lawrence covers the stumps and shoulders arms to that one.

Good-length ball but well outside off, swinging away further. Dan Lawrence leaves it alone.

Good-length ball, outside off, some extra bounce off the deck. Joe Root looks to defend it out but gets beaten on the outside edge. This got a smile on Root's face.
A full-length ball, on off. Joe Root drives it to the left of the bowler with soft hands. Kemar Roach does really well to bend down and stop the ball.
Full length, outside off. Joe Root leaves it alone for the keeper.
Full and shaping into the pads, Root hangs back and blocks it out.
Top delivery! A good-length ball, in the corridor of uncertainty. It flies off the deck. Joe Root tries to defend it out but does not get anywhere near the ball.
Well wide of off, Dan Lawrence lets it be. A successful over for Jayden Seales. A wicket-maiden!
Dan Lawrence is the new batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! WHAT A STUNNING CATCH BY JOSHUA DA SILVA. England's opening woes continue. They have lost both their openers inside 4 overs. Jayden Seales gets himself into the wicket's column now. A full-length ball, outside off. Zak Crawley stays inside the crease and tries to drive it towards mid on but without any movement. The ball takes the inside edge and stays very low. It scoots past the off-pole and goes to the left of Joshua Da Silva, behind the sticks. He makes a full-stretched dive to his left by hanging his left hand out and luckily for him the ball stays in his glove. Brilliant bowling and even better keeping from Joshua Da Silva. This is a sensational start from West Indies!
Commentary.Howout: c Joshua Da Silva b Jayden Seales

Jayden Seales bowls from wide of the crease and serves a full-length ball, in the corridor of uncertainty. Zak Crawley covers the stumps and leaves it alone for the keeper.

The England skipper, Joe Root walks in at number 3.

England have opted a review for an LBW. UltraEdge shows there is a flat line as the ball passes the bat. Ball Tracking shows that the ball is pitching outside off, the impact is umpire's call and it is wickets hitting. So, England retain their review but Alex Lees will have to depart as the original decision stands.

OUT! LBW! England do not lose a review but they do lose a wicket. Alex Lees' debut innings comes to an end early. Kemar Roach sets up Lees beautifully and gets the better of him. A length ball, around off, comes in with the angle. Alex Lees tries to defend it out on his front foot but gets pinged on the front pad. Kemar Roach appeals and the umpire raises his finger after giving it some thought. Alex Lees is not pleased as he thinks it is bat first and takes the review. The UltraEdge shows no bat is involved. The Ball Tracking shows it is umpire's call on impact as the ball goes to knock the stumps off. In the end, the on-field decision stands and Alex Lees trudges back to the pavilion.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Kemar Roach

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, outside off, it nips away a touch off the deck. Alex Lees has no interest in playing away from his body.
Good-length ball, outside off. It holds its line after hitting the deck. Alex Lees shuffles across a bit and shoulders his arms at it.
Back of a length, outside off. Zak Crawley leaves it alone for the keeper. England are off to a positive start.
FOUR! Width on offer this time and Crawley does not shy away at all. It is full and wide outside off. Zak Crawley leans in and drives it through the cover region for a boundary. He moves to 8.
A length ball, angling down leg. Zak Crawley tries to flick it away but misses. The ball brushes his pads and goes to the left of the keeper.
FOUR! It is a trademark Zak Crawley! A full-length ball, on the fourth stump line. Zak Crawley gets behind the line and drives it down the ground to bag a boundary.
A length ball, on the fifth stump line. Zak Crawley covers his stumps and leaves it alone for the keeper.
Jayden Seales starts with a fuller delivery, angled down leg. Zak Crawley looks to flick it away but misses. Joshua Da Silva dives to his left behind the sticks to make a great stop.
Jayden Seales to operate from the other end.
Good length, outside off, shaping away. Alex Lees has nothing to do with it.

FOUR! Alex Lees gets off the mark with a glorious stroke. He opens his account in International cricket and also this series. A full-length ball, outside off. Alex Lees plays it late and guides it past the point fielder for a boundary.
A length ball, outside off. Lees shoulders his arms at it.
Three dots on the trot! Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Alex Lees shuffles across and tries to defends it out but ends up keeping the blade close to his body.
An outswinger, full and on off. Alex Lees stays inside the crease and defends it out solidly.
A little bit of swing to start with. Roach serves a back-of-a-length delivery, outside off. It shapes away a bit. Alex Lees leaves it alone for the keeper.

We are done with the pre-match formalities. The players now stride out to the middle. Alex Lees, the Durham debutant is set to open alongside Zak Crawley. Kemar Roach to start the proceedings with the ball. Before he steams in, the players take a knee in support of the BLM movement. Let's go. Three slips and a gully in place for Roach.

Both the teams stride out to the middle and lineup for the national anthem. Both sides are wearing black armbands to show respect for Shane Warne, Rod Marsh and Sunny Ramadin. First, the national anthem of England will be played followed by West Indies'.

PITCH REPORT - Sir Curtly Ambrose says that once the early moisture is gone, the pitch will become good for batting. Says that there is not much grass on it as well. Mark Butcher reckons that the pitch should dry out and open up a few cracks with first-innings runs being the key.

Joe Root, the English skipper, is in for a chat. He says, they will bat first. Mentions the pitch looks very dry. Also says that the first session would be very crucial, as the condition may deterioate through the game. Kraigg Brathwaite, the West Indies skipper joins the chat. He says, they are thinking about the processes. They will try to stick to their plans and everything should fall in place. Mentions, the boys are really hungry and it should be a good contest. Adds that there is a spinner, Veerasammy Permaul, along with four quicks.

West Indies (Playing XI) - Kraigg Brathwaite (C), John Campbell, Shamarh Brooks, Nkrumah Bonner, Jermaine Blackwood, Jason Holder, Joshua Da Silva (WK), Alzarri Joseph, Kemar Roach, Veerasammy Permaul, Jayden Seales.
England (Playing XI) - Zak Crawley, Alex Lees (On debut), Joe Root (C), Dan Lawrence, Ben Stokes, Jonny Bairstow, Ben Foakes (WK), Chris Woakes, Craig Overton, Mark Wood, Jack Leach.
TOSS - The coin goes up and lands in favour of England. They have opted to BAT first.

England on the other hand, would be raring to go as they have a point to prove in this series after a humiliating 0-4 thrashing in the Ashes series Down Under. The humiliating campaign also propelled many major changes in the England squad. Hence, it will be interesting to see how the side fares against West Indies. Notably, England’s last visit to the Caribbean Islands wasn’t memorable as they suffered a 1-2 defeat in the Test series. Joe Root's men will be definitely eager to perform better and would be eyeing nothing but a win. Will the Windies put up a show? Will they hand a defeat? How well will England fare without Anderson and Broad? Can England forget the Ashes demons and play with more fight and determination? So many questions. The answer to all of them will become clear soon. Stick around for toss and team news.

West Indies' last assignment was the limited overs tour to India where they failed to win even a single game. Before that, they played 5 T20Is against England and won the series 3-2. They haven't played any red ball cricket off late and their last series came against Sri Lanka which they lost 2-0. They would be hoping to turn their fortunes this time around. They would be keen to bring on their A game and kick off the series on a winning note at their own backyard.

There are some enthralling series in action in the red-ball cricket and now here we are to entertain you with another coverage as England take on the West Indies. Both teams have their own flaws to battle in this format and are also at the bottom of the World Test Championship table. Both sides have some exciting players on their side and an intense battle can be expected over the course of the next five days. On that note, welcome to the coverage of the first Test.
... DAY 1, SESSION 1 ...

All in readiness for England's second innings. The players are out in the middle. Alex Lees and Zak Crawley are the openers for England. A quick fix up is going on as a roller is used on the pitch. Kemar Roach has the ball in his hand. Here we go...
...Third innings....

UPDATE - 7.37 pm IST (2.07 pm GMT) - Meanwhile, the pitch is covered right now due to a slight drizzle. The umpire has his umbrella out as well. Looks like a passing shower. And....the covers are coming off.

This is what England needed. An early wicket, just the three deliveries that were needed for England to bundle things out and they have not allowed the tail to wag much. In the end it was a good bowling display from England. Their bowlers had to toil hard and put an extra shift as well, courtesy of the unavailability of Mark Wood. Jack Leach bowled with probing lines while Ben Stokes asked questions regularly. Now, England batters need to get a good start and the first target would be to try and get a lead in the first session.  West Indies lead by 64 runs and they'll hope to run through this fragile English line-up...

OUT! LBW! That is plumb in front! Leach tosses it up, on a length, just outside off. Jayden Seales prods to defend but he misses and gets rapped on his pad as he plays down the wrong line. England appeal and the umpire agrees. Seales though, opts for a review but the Ball Tracker indicates three reds and Seales is a goner. West Indies are bowled out for 375!
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Jack Leach

Commentary.Commentary: Review! England have got the wicket early on but Jayden Seales has taken it upstairs. Three reds and that is the end of the Windies batting.
Tosses it up, around off. Jayden Seales blocks it off the front foot.
TWO BYES! West Indies are underway on Day 4! Flatter ball, outside off. Jayden Seales leaves it and the keeper fails to grab it cleanly. The batters collect a couple of byes.
We are all set for the action. Joe Root leads his troop while Jayden Seales and Veerasammy Permaul will continue their innings. Spin to start the proceedings as Jack Leach has the ball.

PITCH REPORT - Samuel Badree and Mark Butcher are near the pitch. Butcher says that there are a few cracks on the pitch but it has played well so far. Tells that we can expect the pitch to misbehave a bit on Day 4. Badree says that there might be some variable bounce on offer and the spinners will come into play. Mentions that one side of the pitch is better than the other but it isn't easy to bat on it.

West Indies lead by 62 runs. Bonner made sure they boss the third Day as he stitched crucial partnerships with everyone. Bonner was all set to continue his innings but fell to a part-timer and will be gutted with that. The hosts would be hoping that their overnight batters bat as long as possible and extend the lead. Stay tuned for further updates as we are in for an intriguing first session.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 4 of the first Test between England and West Indies. The English bowlers toiled hard in a breezy sunny day as they were made to work hard to take wickets of the Windies' batters. On top of that, they had to put in extra shift as Mark Wood was not seen after Lunch on Day 3, might be due to right elbow issue. They will hope to take the last wicket on Day 4 as soon as possible and not allow West Indies to run away with the lead.

Right then! Day 3 proved to be slow and sluggish but that wicket right at the death might just turn out to be the spark this match needed. There's still plenty of time left in this Test match and it all depends on either team deciding to press the issue. If that does happen, the last couple of days might turn out to be the most interesting and exciting. Action on Day 4 will begin at 7.30 pm IST (2 pm GMT). Join us for the build up early though. See you then. Cheers!

The man of the hour, Nkrumah Bonner is up for a quick chat. He says the century it means a lot. Adds, he was looking at the stats and the team needed him to step up today. Tells, they need to bat an hour more tomorrow before putting the pressure on the English batters. On his wicket, he says that he might have played too casually and is a little disappointed.

Well, England let their advantage slip on Day 2 but they had the experienced Holder back in the hut in the first 15 minutes of play today and seemed to have regained the lost advantage. They slipped up again though and wickets have been a luxury that England have found really expensive to afford. They were not aided by the fact that Mark Wood was ruled out from bowling in the innings completely due to a shoulder issue. Ben Stokes has certainly been their best bowler and Jack Leach kept on probing and probing all day long. Overton too bowled well in patches and used the short ball well at times. Woakes didn't create many chances for his side and being a bowler down, the visitors felt deflated. In the end, in a desperate effort just to see out the day, Dan Lawrence was brought on to bowl and he ended up picking the prized wicket of Bonner about 10 minutes before the close of play. It has been a long day for England in the field and they will have to go back to the drawing board and draw out some inspiration when they take the field tomorrow morning or else a day's disappointment might turn into defeat.

Moving day? At what pace though? Day 3 has gone by slowly with only 171 runs being scored off 90.1 overs and it has been a long and hard toil by the English bowlers. West Indies trailed by 109 runs at the start of the day and had 6 wickets in hand. They have ended the day with still 1 wicket remaining and lead by 62 runs. Given the full 90 overs were bowled and there was nothing in it for the bowlers, the hosts have surely scored at a very low rate but they do have the edge. Nkrumah Bonner has certainly been the star of the show, he had been out there for well over 500 minutes and not once did he look like slacking, well that is until he got out on 123 very, very late in the day that too by a part-time bowler. Tremendous concentration was shown by him and even the tail-enders did a brilliant job to play 50 plus balls with ease. The hosts have certainly frustrated their opponents but will look to change gears tomorrow morning if they want to try and win this game.

Is Dan Lawrence going to be the golden arm for England? Joe Root has reviewed a caught behind decision. UltraEdge shows that Nkrumah Bonner got the finest of tickles on that one and the onfield decision is overturned. Lawrence does prove to be the golden arm and the English players and spectators are mightily relieved.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Finally, Nkrumah Bonner long, long defensive show is over. What an innings this is from him. 355 deliveries faced, wow! A full ball, sliding down the leg side. Bonner looks to flick but seems to miss it. An appeal for caught behind but nothing given. Lawrence convinces Root to take it upstairs and they go for it. UltraEdge shows a small spike as the ball passes the blade and the on-field decision is changed. A soft-dismissal rather to be honest but Bonner was nodding. The change of bringing Dan Lawrence just worked for Root. Worked more than wonders. His second wicket in Test cricket.

West Indies lost two wickets in this session and scored 51 runs but the good thing is Nkrumah Bonner is still out there edging to his century. Kemar Roach is doing well to give him support and he too looks well settled now. A worrying sign for England as Mark Wood was not seen in this session at all and unlikely as well due to a right elbow issue. His pace and bouncer right now would have worked against this lower order but now Joe Root has to put up his thinking cap. Jack Leach was bowling quite nicely but it was a brilliant defensive display from the Windies batters. England will look to bundle West Indies out in the last and final session of the day but they need something special for it. Do join us for the final session at 12:30 am IST (7 am GMT)

Shorter and on middle, played on the leg side.
A slower length ball, outside off and nipping back in. Roach taps it to point.
On middle. Defended out.
Bangs a bouncer now, on middle. Roach lets it through.
Short of a length, on middle. Bonner pulls it to deep square leg for a single. Too casual running from Nkrumah Bonner. He looks a bit weary.
Length ball, outside off. Bonner defends with hard hands, uppishly and to point.
Length ball, at 121 kph, around off. Blocked out.
Craig Overton (24-5-74-2) is brought back into the attack.
Touch fuller, angling on middle. A straight bat defensive push back to the bowler.
Full and on middle, pushed to covers.
Short of a length, outside off. Roach hangs his bat out but the ball goes well over it.
A low dipping full toss, on off, pushed to covers.
On middle, on a length. Bonner tucks it wide of square leg for a run.

Ian Bishop (the onfield commentator) states that Mark Wood might not bowl at all in this innings again. This might be a huge issue for England as Wood receives treatment to his right elbow. With Wood's pace, it certainly would have been a bit easier to trouble the tail-enders.
Length and on the pads. Bonner flicks it to mid-wicket.
Another solid block to end the over.
Slides a length ball, on middle. Kept out.
An arm ball, flatter and angling around middle. Roach defends it on the front foot.
Around off, it is hit to covers for one.
FOUR! Well played! Tossed up, full and on middle. Bonner sweeps it in the gap to square leg for a boundary.
Flatter and around off. Bonner defends it on the off side.
Slants a full delivery, on middle. Roach blocks it out.
Angles it on the pads. Bonner works it to square leg for a single.
This is on middle. Bonner is happy to show his defensive skills.
Length and on middle. Bonner tucks it off the inner half to square leg.
Length and on off, pushed back to the bowler.
Woakes serves a beautiful yorker, on middle and Bonner gets his bat down in time.
Floated up, on off. Kemar Roach puts out a big stride forward to defend.
On middle, driven past a diving mid on fielder for a single. West Indies trail by just 20 runs now.
A bit flighted, on off. Bonner drives it straight towards covers.
Flatter, angled into middle and leg. Worked towards mid-wicket by Bonner.
On off, turning away. Played with the spin towards covers.
Slower through the air, around off. Bonner waits for it and dabs it towards first slip.
On middle, kept out towards mid-wicket.
Well-directed short ball, over middle. Kemar Roach does well to duck under that one. The ball comes off the shoulder of the batter and that must have stung a bit.
Length this time, slanting into off. Roach defends it out.
Pitched up, outside off. Roach shoulders arms to that one.
Fullish delivery, around off. Roach looks to cover drive away from the body and gets an inside edge towards short mid-wicket.
This is banged in over middle. Bonner pulls it along the ground towards deep square leg and picks up a single.
Good from Nkrumah Bonner, picking up the single off the final delivery. Tossed up, on off. Bonner uses his feet and pushes it towards mid off for a quick single.
Around middle and leg, Bonner goes deep in the crease and keeps it down past short leg.
Darted into middle this time. Bonner keeps it out.
Quicker, on off. This is pushed back towards the bowler.
Flatter this time, on a nagging length and around off. Bonner goes back and across to block.
This is drifted onto middle and leg. Bonner blocks it out.

Drinks! It has been much better from England after Lunch. Their bowlers have come out with a clear-cut plan and have executed it well enough. The two wickets have dried up the runs and the game hangs nicely in the balance. Nkrumah Bonner is the key for West Indies and it will be interesting to see at what point does he start to take on the English bowlers. Jack Leach (24-13-48-1) is back on.
Good-length, over off. Blocked out.
Stokes hits the length hard and bowls it on middle. Roach manages to keep it down on the leg side.
On middle and leg, tucked away to mid-wicket.
Length this time, angled into off. Roach gets right behind the line of the ball to make the block.
Full and on off. Bonner drives it towards mid off and scampers through for a quick single.
Around off, pushed out on the off side.
Pitched up, on middle. Roach blocks it out.
Fuller and trying to slant it into middle and leg. Kemar Roach works it through mid-wicket off the inner half of the bat and picks up a couple of runs to get off the mark.
Right on the money from Chris Woakes! Roach stays solid in defense though.
Just a tad bit short and this is jabbed down to deep mid-wicket for just a single.
A length ball, around off. Bonner taps it towards short cover.
On off, blocked out by Bonner.
This is slanted into the pads. Roach manages to keep it down to the left of the short leg fielder.
Full and angling into off. Roach plays a solid defensive shot.
Short ball, on the body. This is pulled down to deep backward square leg for a single.
Length, on off. Bonner hangs back and pushes it towards mid off.
This is fuller and angled into middle and leg. Bonner does well to flick it leg side.
Around the top of off, this is pushed towards mid on.

Banged in, around the body. Roach tucks it away to deep mid-wicket and there's an easy single on offer. Nkrumah Bonner knowing that it's the last ball of the over, denies him and Roach has a smile on his face. He would have loved to get off the mark here.
Woakes hits the length hard and angles it down the leg side. No shot offered.
Peach! Pitched up, outside off and this one slants in a long way. Kemar Roach gets beaten past the outside edge again and Ben Foakes collects the ball past the leg stump.

How did that miss the off pole? This is pitched up, around off and the ball comes in with the angle. Roach goes on the back foot and gets beaten past the outside edge. The ball somehow goes a whisker over the off stump as well.
Halt in play. Kemar Roach gets hit on his right gloves and needs some assistance from the physio. Some magic spray is applied...

Nicely bowled! A length ball, on off and this one lands right on the seam and takes off. Kemar Roach looks to push at it but the extra bounce surprises him a bit and the ball goes off the thumb towards the slip cordon. Roach seems to be in some pain here.
Full and straight, Nkrumah Bonner digs it out towards mid off and picks up a single.
Chris Woakes is back on.
Good-length, on off. Roach stays solid in defense and it will be a fourth maiden on the trot for England.
Nice follow-up delivery from Overton. A slower yorker, floated in around off stump. Roach does well to keep it out.

That's a nasty one for Kemar Roach. Banged into the deck around off. This is at 123 kph and just doesn't bounce that higher. Roach tries to sway away from the line of the ball but instead gets a body blow.
Full and on the pads. Roach tucks it away to backward leg.
This is banged in over middle and leg. Kemar Roach ducks under it.
Fullish ball, bowled in that channel around off and angling in. The ball holds its line after pitching and Roach gets beaten past the outside edge.
On middle and leg, Bonner looks to drive but mistimes it to the right of the bowler as Leach makes a good diving stop. Yet another maiden over and the Windies starting to get bogged down here.
Drifting into middle and leg. Bonner goes on the back foot and keeps it down to short leg.
Full, around off. This is pushed towards the cover region.
Flatter this time, on off. Defended nicely by Bonner.
Quicker and fuller, drifted into middle. Bonner goes on the back foot to keep this one out.
Quicker, darted into middle. Bonner strides out to defend.
This is spilled down the leg side, Roach gets no bat on it. Back-to-back maiden overs for the visitors.
Length this time, angled into middle and leg. Roach keeps it down on the leg side.
This is fuller and angled down leg. Roach looks to tuck but misses and the ball dies on the way to the keeper.
This time the ball doesn't bounce high enough. This is banged in on middle, Roach looks to duck under it again but the ball just about goes over his helmet.
And again! This time over middle and leg. Roach with another easy duck.
More short stuff from Overton. Over middle, Roach ducks under it.

Dropped! What a chance for England! This is full and angling on the pads. Bonner looks to heave it on the leg side but gets a thin inside edge onto the pads and to first slip where Zak Crawley makes a meal of it. First it looked like there was no bat but UltaEdge confirms bat on it.
Slightly fuller and on off. Bonner steps across and defends it out.
Tossed up, on middle. Kept out.
Very full and on middle, pushed towards mid on, not in the gap though.
Outside off, pushed to covers.
Flatter and on middle. Defended out.
Kemar Roach walks in at number 9.

OUT! TAKEN! If Nkrumah Bonner is not tempted, Alzarri Joseph gets into the trap here. Brilliant from England! A short ball again, angling on middle. Alzarri Joseph goes for the pull but gets a top edge to fine leg where Ollie Pope, the substitute fielder comes forward and takes it low. England trying to bundle things quickly. West Indies trail by 29 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c sub Ollie Pope b Craig Overton

Commentary.Commentary: Touch short this time, on leg. Bonner pulls it, off his gloves and to fine leg for a single.
Short ball again but Nkrumah Bonner is not tempted to go for the pull shot. Lets it through to the keeper.
A length ball, angling on the pads, tucked to mid-wicket for a run.
Short again and Joseph ducks under it.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone.
Tossed up, on middle. Bonner stays back to defend it out.
Alzarri Joseph is off the mark! Flatter ball, outside off. Joseph punches with an angled bat, wide of first slip and they get a single.
On middle. Blocked out.
Shorter and outside off. Joseph punches it to covers.
Alzarri Joseph is the new man in at the crease.

OUT! LBW! Leach serves a tossed up delivery, angling around middle and leg. Da Silva goes on the back foot to flick it but misses and gets hit slightly high on the pads. An appeal and up goes the finger. Da Silva takes the review quickly and the replay shows no bat involved but Ball Tracking shows the ball is going onto hit the top of the leg pole. Jack Leach is finally rewarded for his persistence.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Jack Leach

Commentary.Commentary: This is the second time Joshua Da Silva has been adjudged LBW and again he straightaway signals for the review. Da Silva is on the back foot and he reckons it's too high. UltraEdge shows that there's no bat involved. Ball Tracker comes up with three reds as the ball is going on to hit the top of leg stump. Finally, England have the breakthrough and Da Silva's resistance comes to an end.
Flatter ball, outside off. Left alone.
On a length, outside off, good pace there. Bonner defends with a straight bat but gets an outside edge to point.
Craig goes wide of the crease and angles a short ball, on leg. Da Silva tickles it off the gloves and the keeper fumbles to collect it. A single taken.
A short ball and on middle. Da Silva sits under it. A wide given for height.
On middle, on a length. Blocked out.
England and Craig Overton going full in for this short-ball play. A short leg has now also been put in place and there's a catcher in the deep for the hook.
Short ball, hitting the pitch hard and Da Silva evades it well.
Length ball, on off. Da Silva defends it.
Short and on middle, pulled away to square leg for a single. Da Silva is jogging across and that tempts Ben Stokes to have a shy at the bowler's end. No one backing up and they get another single.
Around off, pushed to covers.
Slightly short, on middle. Bonner hits it on the leg side.
Tossed up, on middle and Bonner on the back foot, blocks it out. Jack Leach is getting turn here.
Fuller and on middle. Bonner dead-bats it.
Shorter and on off, pushed to covers.
Short ball, outside off. Bonner waits and cuts it late past backward point. The fielder gives a chase and slides it back near the ropes. The batters take two runs.
On middle, tucked to mid-wicket.
A length ball, going down. It does not bounce much and takes the ads off Da Silva who leaves it alone. Good take by Foakes behind.
Back of a length, on off. Da Silva hops and keeps it out.
A short ball but angling down the leg side. Da Silva ducks under it.
Length ball, outside off. Bonner punches and beats the man at gully for a single.
Bangs a short ball, around middle and leg. Bonner sits under it.
Craig Overton (19-3-67-1) to bowl from the opposite end.
Down the leg side and Da Silva leaves it alone.
This one lands around leg and spins a touch away. Da Silva is aware and defends it solidly.
Tossed up, drifting on the pads. Da Silva goes back and tucks it towards short leg.
Tossed up, on off. Da Silva drops it on the off side.
Fuller and on middle. Joshua Da Silva keeps it out.
Flatter ball, on off. Bonner goes back in his crease and punches it through point for a single. West Indies are offf the mark in this session.

We are back for the post-Lunch session. The players and the umpires are out in the middle. Nkrumah Bonner and Joshua Da Silva take guard. Jack Leach has the ball in hand and he will start proceedings after the break.
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

Right then. A session that started off with a bang for the visitors has ended with the hosts looking fairly comfortable. It will be interesting to see how England try to get the two set batters out. Also, will Da Silva and Bonner take the game to the English bowlers and put their side in the lead at the earliest? With the lead being cut down to just 40 runs, expect a few risks from the bowling side. An intriguing session coming up after the break. Join us back at 10:10 pm IST (4:40 pm GMT).

Jason Holder is up for a quick chat. He says they had a good session. Adds it is a straight pitch and he feels the runs will come. Tells, his wicket took the toe end of the bat and he is disappointed with it. Also mentions the wicket is easy and there is no spin as well, rough at one side of the pitch. Says that one more hour like this will be very crucial and hopes they make the English bowlers work hard as he feels the runs will come then.

England will not be pleased as the sides go off the field for a Lunch break. Overall they bowled well throughout the session but once Ben Stokes provided them the early breakthrough, they just couldn't capitalize. The pacers hardly created any chances and sometimes the line was too wide and easy for the Windies batters to leave. Woakes was fairly economical and Wood peppered the opposition with a few short balls but on a pitch that seems a bit dead, the ball needs to be consistently pitched up and around the off stump. Stokes was certainly the best bowler in the first session and the visitors will hope to regroup and bundle out the opposition before it's too late.

West Indies will certainly be the happier of the two sides heading into the Lunch interval. The repair work had been done last evening by Nkrumah Bonner and Jason Holder but the latter couldn't prolong his stay at the crease for too long. He was undone by a beauty from Stokes early in the day and it seemed like the hosts will succumb further. That wasn't the case though as even when the runs were hard to come by, Joshua Da Silva and Bonner hardly played a false shot and just kept on leaving the good balls. In the last half an hour of the session, both of them started finding the gaps and have brought the lead down to just 40 runs with 5 wickets still in hand.
Alength ball, slanting on middle. Bonner wrists it to square leg and takes a single. That will be Lunch on Day 3.
Fuller ball, coming into the right-hander. Bonner with an easy leave.
Length outside off, and left alone.
Length ball, angling on middle. Bonner hits it through the line to mid on.
Around off, fuller and pushed wide of mid off for a single.
Short ball, on middle. Da Silva pulls it hard and to the left of deep square leg. Ollie Pope has to run quickly there and puts a dive to save a couple of runs. Good fielding.
Strays it on the pads, flicked to square leg for a single.
Slightly short, slower in the air and hint of spin as well. Da Silva lunges to defend but gets an outside edge wide of first slip to third man for a brace.
A single as this is pushed through covers.
Angles a fuller ball, on off. Bonner guides it straight to point.
Fuller ball, outside off. Da Silva pushes with the spin, through covers for a single.
Flatter ball, around off. Bonner punches off the back foot to deep cover for a single.
Length ball, straying around middle and off. Da Silva prods and defends it.
Short of a length, slanting around off. Da Silva hops and pulls it, not off the middle and hits it over mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Fuller ball, outside off, swinging away and Da Silva lets it be.
A length ball, angling on middle. Da Silva solidly blocks it.
Length and on off. Blocked out.
Full toss, outside off. Da Silva pushes it to the left of mid off.
Ben Stokes (14-0-27-2) to bowl now.
Quicker and shorter, around off. Bonner rocks back and cuts it through cover-point. Craig Overton chases it from cover and keeps it down to a couple. The runs flowing nicely now for the hosts.
Too short and wide from Leach. Bonner rocks back and taps it with the spin through the cover region for a brace. The 50 partnership also comes up between these two.
FOUR! A confident-looking sweep shot from Nkrumah Bonner. Flatter, on off. Bonner gets down on one knee and sweeps it hard and low, past short leg for a boundary.
Nicely drifted into off, the ball turns away a bit. Bonner leaves it alone in the end.
Short again, around middle. Da Silva goes deep in his crease to work it through mid-wicket for a run.
Shorter in length, outside off. Joshua Da Silva hops on the back foot and punches it towards cover.
Jack Leach (17-11-29-0) is back into the attack.
Back of a length, around off. This is pushed away on the off side for a single. The 250 comes up for West Indies.

Now, Chris Woakes does get one to nip back in and it's a peach of a delivery. Woakes goes wide of the crease and angles it in from well outside off. The ball nips back in and Joshua Da Silva gets cut in half. The ball clips the top of the pad and the bowler seems interested. Nothing given and they don't go for the review as the impact might have been outside off. Indeed it was, as the replays confirm the same.
Lovely shape on that one! Length, angled into middle. The ball nips away off the surface. Da Silva though stays solid in defense.
Angled into off, but leaving the batter after pitching. Da Silva makes a watchful leave.
On a length, around the top of off. Da Silva hangs back and keeps it out towards short cover.
Pitched up, well outside off. The batter isn't going to play at that one.
Much better from Wood. Length, hitting the top of middle. Bonner blocks it solidly off the front foot.
Good-length, over middle. Joshua Da Silva shuffles a bit and tickles it 'round the corner for a single.
Pitched up, on off. Da Silva presents a dead bat at it.
Back of a length, on off. Da Silva defends it off the back foot.
This is banged into the deck, on the body. Bonner fends it away on the leg side and collects a run.

SIX! England's lead is diminishing sooner rather than later. Wood comes back in and starts off with a wayward delivery on the hips. Nkrumah Bonner uses the pace and swings at it. The ball goes off the top edge and flies over the fine leg fence.
Mark Wood (16-4-37-1) replaces Craig Overton now.
Back of a length, over off. Joshua Da Silva hangs back and keeps it down on the off side. Yet another maiden for Chris Woakes.
Pitched up, around off. Da Silva leans in and nudges it towards point with soft hands.
Woakes hits the length hard this time and bowls it around off. Da Silva taps it back onto the deck off the back foot.
This is angled into middle and leg, Da Silva tucks it towards short mid-wicket.
Full and angled into the off stump. Da Silva does well to get a bat on it.
A length ball, well outside off. Da Silva leaves it alone.
Full and wide this time, guided towards backward point.
Full, around off and shaping in. Bonner defends it out.
A tad bit short, on off. Da Silva pulls it through mid-wicket for a single.

NOT OUT! Brilliant review from Joshua Da Silva and he survives. Fullish delivery, angled in from around off. The ball pitches and nips back in a long way. Da Silva shuffles right across the stumps and his head seems to be falling over. He misses the tuck and gets pinged on the pads. Da Silva reviews it straightaway. UltraEdge shows that there's no bat involved and Ball Tracker shows that the ball was in fact doing a bit too much and missing leg stump by a few inches.

Review time! Joshua Da Silva takes the LBW decision upstairs. UltraEdge shows no bat involved. Ball Tracking shows the ball goes onto missing the leg stump. Wonderful review from Joshua Da Silva, he was confident about it.
Length, angled into off. Da Silva keeps it out towards short mid-wicket.
Huge inward movement this time but after the ball passes the batter. Well outside off, Da Silva with an easy leave.
Pitched up, in that channel outside off but shaping away. Bonner with another good leave. Back-to-back maidens for Chris Woakes.
This is pitched up, on off. Bonner is forced to play at that one and defends it out towards mid off.
Full again but wide of the off pole. Bonner can leave deliveries like that one all day long.
Fullish delivery, angled into middle. Bonner defends it off the front foot.
Well bowled and well left! This is angled in from wide of the crease and the ball zips away off the surface. Bonner watches it all the way through and leaves it alone.
Full and wide, Bonner isn't interested in playing at that one.
Uppish but in the gap! Short of a length, on off. Da Silva doesn't get hold of the pull shot but manages to hit it well wide of short mid-wicket to collect a couple of runs.
Right on the money this time! Around the top of off. Solidly defended by Joshua Da Silva.
A length ball, outside off. Left alone by Da Silva.
Nicely driven for two more. Overpitched, around off. Da Silva presses forward and strokes it through extra cover for a brace.
Full and on the pads. Joshua Da Silva works it in front of square on the leg side and picks up a couple of runs.
This is spilled way down the leg side. Good takes from the keeper.

Hint of away movement from Craig Overton. Length, on off and just nipping away off the surface. Da Silva gets caught on the crease and gets rapped high on the pads. It is given as a no ball as Overton oversteps.
Maiden over! Pitched up, close to the off stump and shaping away nicely. Bonner shoulders arms to that one.
Fuller this time, on middle and shaping away just a bit. Bonner blocks it out.
Woakes hits the length hard and angles it from around off. Bonner stays solid in defense.
And again! This is a bit further away from the off stump and it's an easier leave for Bonner.
Well left! Full and angled into off stump. The ball shapes away at the last moment and Nkrumah Bonner makes a watchful leave. The ball zips through to the keeper as well.
Full and well outside off. No need to play at that one.
Full again, around off. Da Silva squeezes it out towards point.
Fifty for Nkrumah Bonner and this has been a fine, fine knock. Full, angled in from wide of the crease. Bonner pushes it out towards cover and picks up a single.
Around the top of off. Bonner hangs back and bunts it out on the off side.
Full again, on off. Bonner defends it back towards the bowler.
Pitched up, in that corridor of uncertainty. Bonner leaves it alone.
Overton starts off with a length ball, on leg stump and swinging further down. Ben Foakes does well to dive to his left and stop the ball.
New cherry is taken and straightaway Craig Overton (16-3-58-1) is called back to bowl.
Joshua Da Silva walks towards the bowler and gets right behind the line of the ball to make the block.
Angling in from outside off and leaving the right-hander. Watchful leave by Da Silva.
Full again, around off. Da Silva shoulders arms to this one.
FOUR! Edgy boundary! A bit fuller, around off and there is away movement this time. Da Silva pushes at it and gets an outside edge past the slip cordon for a boundary.
This is angled into middle and leg, looking for the dream outswinging delivery. Joshua Da Silva gets right behind the line to block.
Good-length this time, outside off and the ball holds its line. Da Silva with another leave.

Woakes starts off with a fullish delivery, wide of the off pole and this one shapes away nicely. Da Silva with an easy leave though. Also, Woakes has overstepped and starts his new spell with a no ball.

Drinks! It started off as a pretty good session for the visitors as they kept a lid on the runs and Ben Stokes got the big wicket of Jason Holder to put the hosts on the back foot. Joshua Da Silva has been providing ample support to Nkrumah Bonner who is now starting to play his shots as well and the Windies trail by 84 runs at the moment. The second ball is also now available but this old ball is still reversing just a bit. Will Joe Root take the second new ball straightaway or will he wait a couple of overs? So, the new ball is taken and Chris Woakes will try and make the most of it.
Short in length, outside off. Bonner again wants to pull but fails this time.
FOUR! Bonner making the most of the old ball here! Short again, outside off. Bonner hits it aerially and through point for another boundary.
FOUR! Cries of 'catch it' but this went through the gap! Short of a length, on middle. Bonner gets on top of the bounce and pulls it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
Wood comes over the wicket and bowls it on a length, on middle. Da Silva shuffles across and tucks it through short leg for a single.
A length ball, around middle. Da Silva pushes it to mid on.
Short in length, on off. Da Silva hops and blocks it on the off side.
Slightly full and on middle. Bonner comes forward to keep it out.
Flatter ball, this one straightens off the deck. Bonner prods and defends it.
Fuller and on off. Bonner leans and pushes it to covers.
Now goes back and punches it to point.
Flatter and on off, pushed to covers.
Leg bye! An appeal for LBW but that was going down the leg side. Leach gets drift in the air as he serves it fuller and on the pads. Da Silva misses his flick. It goes off the pads to square leg.
Jack Leach (16-10-29-0) is back on with the second new ball being available after a couple of more overs.
Goes wide of the crease, on a length and outside off. Da Silva steers it to third man for  asingle.
Late movement there, outside off and coming back in. Da Silva offers no shot.
A bouncer now, outside off. Silva dodges it easily.
Length this time, angled into middle and leg. Da Silva pushes it to short mic-wicket.
What happened here? A slower bumper, at just 117 clicks. Joshua Da Silva has his feet off the ground as he looks to fend it away. The ball though bounces over his head and Da Silva is a relieved man.
Back of a length, on off. Da Silva hops and defends it back onto the deck.
Length ball, angling on middle. Da Silva hooks it to square leg for a run.
Fuller ball, angling outside off. Silva prods and blocks it.
Length ball, outside off. Silva defends with soft hands and dabs it down off the outer half of the bat, in the gap through the gully region for a couple of runs.
Length ball, going down the leg side. Left alone.
On off, defended out.
Shortish length, on off. Silva on his toes, dead-bats it.
Full ball, straying around middle and Bonner tucks it to mid-wicket. Good probing over from Wood.
Inward movement again, on a length, outside off. Bonner presses forward and blocks it.
Ripper from Wood! Fuller and around off, it lands and nips back in sharply. Bonner is beaten by the movement and gets hit on the pads.
Slightly short, around off. Bonner punches it softly to covers.
Another solid block from Bonner.
Short of a length, on middle. Bonner keeps it out on the leg side.
Fuller this time, outside off. SIlva defends off the back foot.
Length ball, outside off. Bonner taps it to covers for a single.
Outside off again and Bonner shoulders arms to it.
A length ball, outside off, shaping away. Left alone.

Chance! A short ball with extra bounce there, on middle. Nkrumah Bonner miscues his pull shot completely, it goes off the top edge to mid-wicket where Ollie Pope charges forward and dives but fails to take it properly. The ball was dying and Pope had very little time to run forward.
Length ball, on off. Blocked out.
Good seam position there, fuller and on off, pushed back to the bowler.
Short again and Bonner pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a single. The Windies trail by less than 100 runs now.
Bangs a bouncer, outside off. Bonner bottom edges his punch to point.
Length ball, outside off. Silva punches it wide of covers for a single. He is off the mark.
Wood makes the ball move in, around middle but Silva is watchful in his defense.
Wood starts with a fuller ball, straying on the pads. Bonner turns it to deep square leg for one.
Mark Wood (12-3-24-1) is raring to bowl now.
Length and outside off. Defended on the off side.
Full ball, away movement but was way outside off. Easy leave for Silva.
A length ball, outside off. Silva plays it late to catching cover-point.
Slightly full and on middle. Bonner wrists it to deep square leg for one.
Length ball, outside off. Bonner on the front foot, defends it to covers.

In reply, the openers of West Indies found the rhythm quickly and gave a blistering start. Hello and a warm welcome to Day 3 of the first Test between West Indies and England. Both the teams have a good chance to win this match as the match is evenly poised coming into the third-day action. West Indies after losing wickets in a cluster have done well with Nkrumah Bonner and Jason Holder building a partnership of 75. The game looks evenly poised at the moment and Day 3, which is considered as a moving day promises to be a cracking one as both sides will push hard to have the upper hand in this Test. The first ball of Day 3 will be bowled at 7.30 pm IST (2 pm GMT). Do join us then and make sure you tune in early for the buildup. Until then, cheers and goodbye!

Mark Wood is up for a chat. He says that West Indies are in a good position and they need to get early wickets tomorrow. Tells that Holder played really well and he is a fantastic cricketer. Mentions that they need to bowl well tomorrow in the first session and wrap things up quickly. Adds that Bairstow played a crucial knock. Tells that they were poor with the ball in the first session but came back strongly in the second session. Reckons that early wickets will be the key for them tomorrow.

It was West Indies who won the first session as they picked up the remaining wickets quickly, without conceding much runs and then it was the opening stand of Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell which set the tone for them with the bat. Although, once that stand was broken, the hosts lost wickets in a cluster and were in a spot of bother at 127/4. However, Holder and Bonner have fought hard and kept the English bowlers at bay in the third session of Day 2. England came back really well in the second session and grabbed four wickets in quick succession. Their pace bowlers were exceptional in the second session but in spite of toiling hard, they went wicketless in the last session. Jack Leach kept things tight from one end but couldn't go past the set batters.

A good recovery in the third session by West Indies as they had lost 4 wickets for just 44 runs heading into the Tea break. The pair of Jason Holder and Nkrumah Bonner has done exceedingly well to ensure that the hosts end Day 2 on a good note, without losing any more wickets. They have added 75 runs in the last session and West Indies now trail by 109 runs. The English bowlers bowled well in patches and the rain-break didn't help their rhythm either.

A little bit of confusion as the covers weren't being called but the groundsmen still started to bring them on. Eventually, they are being called as the rain has arrived. With that, the umpires have asked the players to leave the field and with that, it is also Stumps on Day 2!

Session Summary - 25.1 overs, 83 runs, 4 wickets. England would be very happy with this session and the Tea is going to taste a lot sweeter for them. The West Indies openers continued from where they left in the morning session and didn't allow the nerves to come onto them. They kept motoring along and meant business. They weren't willing to get bogged down by any stretch but Craig Overton provided his side with the much-needed breakthrough breaking the 83-run stand between John Campbell and Kraigg Brathwaite. And after that, the bowlers started to find their rhythm and got two more wickets. It looked like West Indies would enter Tea without any further hiccups but Chris Woakes struck at the right time and got rid of Jermaine Blackwood. Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell were the only ones who showed courage and fight but they find themselves in a spot of bother now. They would hope that Jason Holder and Nkrumah Bonner see off the last session and remain unscathed. Join us at 12.35 am IST (7.05 pm GMT, previous day) for the final session.
