Fuller in length, around middle. Jermaine Blackwood clips it behind square on the leg side and takes a single. He will retain the strike.
Back of a length, around off. Jermaine Blackwood hangs back and taps it to the off side.
Back of a length, around off. Jermaine Blackwood stays back and punches it towards cover.
A full ball, well outside off. Jermaine Blackwood mistimes his drive to mid off.
A short ball, around off. Jermaine Blackwood ducks underneath.
A short ball, around off. Nkrumah Bonner pulls it along the ground towards deep mid-wicket for a single.
Good-length ball, around off. Jermaine Blackwood defends it off the back foot.
Another ball, on a length and drifting down leg. Jermaine Blackwood misses his nudge on the leg side. A stifled appeal from Wood but nothing from behind the sticks.
Fuller in length, around middle. Jermaine Blackwood flicks it through mid-wicket and comes back for the second run.
Leg bye! A full toss, angling down leg. Nkrumah Bonner misses his flick and the ball brushes off his pad before going to the keeper who half-stops it and the batters get a leg bye.
On a length, around off. Nkrumah Bonner dabs it onto the deck.
Pitches it up, around middle. Nkrumah Bonner prods and nudges it to the leg side.
Wide! A short ball, down leg and above the batter's head. Nkrumah Bonner leaves it and the umpire calls it wide for the height.
A full ball, outside off. Jermaine Blackwood leaves it alone.
Fuller in length, nipping back in from middle. Jermaine Blackwood gets forward and tucks it to mid-wicket.
A full ball, just outside off. Jermaine Blackwood prods and looks to leave it alone but he is a bit late. The ball hits the bottom half of the bat and rolls towards the slip cordon.
Back of a length, around off. Jermaine Blackwood stays back and defends it onto the deck.
A short ball, around middle. Nkrumah Bonner pulls it along the ground towards deep square leg and takes a single.
Good-length ball, around off. Nkrumah Bonner blocks it off the front foot.

Put down! Fuller, outside off. Jermaine Blackwood gets low and looks to drive. The ball goes off the inside edge and goes towards the left of the keeper. A simiar way of how Zak Crawley got out. Ben Foakes dives to his left but fails to grab the catch. Good attempt from him though!
Another short ball, on middle. Jermaine Blackwood ducks under it.
Good-length ball, outside off, jagging back in. Jermaine Blackwood makes a good watchful leave.
Bangs a short ball, on middle. Jermaine Blackwood sits under it comfortably.
On a length, on middle. Jermaine Blackwood nudges it to mid-wicket.
A wayward delivery down the leg side, swinging further away. Nkrumah Bonner leaves it untouched. Ben Foakes dives a long way to his left but fails to collect it cleany. The batters take a bye.
Jermaine Blackwood walks out to bat.

OUT! TAKEN! Since the opening stand of 83 runs has been broken, things have gone in England's favor. Stokes with a beauty this time. Bowls a good-length ball, shaping away from the batter, outside off. Shamarh Brooks has a feel for it. He tries to drive playing away from the body. The ball kisses the outside edge and carries through to Joe Root at first slip. He is all smiles. West Indies lose their third wicket now!
Commentary.Howout: c Joe Root b Ben Stokes

Commentary.Commentary: Short of a length, on middle. Brooks stands tall and blocks it out.
A bouncer, on middle. Brooks sits under it.
Back of a length, on off. Brooks keeps it out.
Short ball, outside off. Brooks lets it be.

FOUR! Vicious delivery from Stokes, short on the off stump, kicks off the turf and hurries Brooks on the backfoot, who drops his bat down but it takes the outside edge and falls short of the second slip as well, runs away down to third-man for a boundary!

NOT OUT! Length ball, outside off. Bonner taps it to point. He calls for a single but is sent back by his partner. The fielder scores a direct hit at the striker's end but Bonner was well in. It is taken upstairs though. Replay shows that Bonner made it home well in time. The third umpire however, shows out on the big screen by mistake and then changes it to not out. A little bit of false hopes given to English fans.
Once again a bouncer that is left by the batsman.
Short of a length, outside off. Brooks punches it towards covers for a single.
Bangs a bouncer again, on middle. Shamarh Brooks sits under it.
Short of a length, on middle. Pulled to deep square leg for a single.
Short ball, outside off. Bonner leaves it for the keeper to collect.
Length ball, tailing back in, outside off. Brooks lets it be.
On a good length, outside off. Brooks again makes a leave.
Good-length ball, outside off. Brooks shoulders arms.
Short ball, outside off. Brooks sways away from the line.
Back of a length, around off. Shamarh Brooks keeps it out.
FOUR! Short of a length, outside off. Shamarh Brooks stays back and runs it past the gully fielder for a boundary.

OUT! CAUGHT! Brilliant catch by Overton! Another breakthrough for England! Wood dishes out a full ball, outside off, at 147 kph. Brathwaite goes chasing for it. The ball catches the outside edge and flies towards gully. Overton there takes a sharp catch. Wood is off to a celebration. They know the importance of this wicket. Brathwaite played a fine knock but has to depart now. England striking back at the right time! Both the openers are back in the hut now. Nkrumah Bonner is the new batsman in.
Commentary.Howout: c Craig Overton b Mark Wood

Commentary.Commentary: On a length, outside off. Blocked out.
Short of a length again, on middle. Brathwaite plays it through mid-wicket for a brace. 100 up for West Indies.
Short of a length, on middle. Brooks hops and clips it to mid-wicket for a single.
Full and on off, Brooks covers the line and defends it back to the bowler.
On a length, on middle and leg. Brathwaite hops and tucks it away to deep mid-wicket. He crosses ends.
On off, driven to short cover.
Length ball, down the leg side. Brooks misses his flick.

NOT OUT! Good-length ball, angling in on middle and leg. Brooks looks to tuck but misses. He gets thudded on the pads. England appeal for an lbw but the umpire shakes his head. Root has a chat with Stokes and goes for the review. UltraEdge shows no bat involved. Ball Tracker shows that it is wickets missing. England lose their review and the original decision stands.
Short ball, outside off. Brooks lets it sail through.

Just short! Length ball, outside off, Brooks goes chasing for it. The ball kisses the outside edge but he plays it with soft hands and as a result, the ball falls just short of the second slip fielder.
Back of a length, on middle. Clipped behind square on the leg side for one.
A bumper this time from Wood, outside off. Brooks lets it sail through.
Another length ball, outside off. Brooks offers no shot to that.
On a good length, outside off. Brooks shoulders arms.
On a length, on middle. Worked to deep mid-wicket for a run
Back of a length, on off. Brathwaite guides it to point.
Short of a length, on middle. Brathwaite clips it on the leg side.
Good-length ball, on off. Brooks defends it out.
Touch fuller this time, outside off. Driven towards covers.
Overpitches it again, on off. Brooks drives it back to the bowler.
Stokes goes full, on off. Brooks plays it straight to short cover.
Good-length ball, on off. Brooks knocks it back to the bowler.

FIFTY! Length ball, on leg. Brathwaite hops and clips it to deep square leg for a single. His 24th Test fifty. This has been a fine knock from the Windies skipper and he will look to add more runs and convert it into a bigger score.
On a length, on off. Brooks stays solid in his defence. Two boundaries then from this over.
On off, kept out by Brooks.
FOUR! Brilliant shot from Brooks again! Stand and deliver stuff! Fuller in length, outside off. Brooks stands tall and drives it past the diving mid off fielder for another boundary.
FOUR! Excellent shot! Short and wide, outside off. A freebie really and Brooks gets on top of the bounce and carves it to deep point for a boundary. He gets off the mark as well.
Full again, on off. Brook uses his feet and flicks it but straight to mid-wicket.
Fuller in length, on off. Brooks leans and drives it towards extra cover.
Shorter, outside off. Tapped to point.
Keeps it full and on middle, Brathwaite presses forward and blocks.
On the pads, flicked to mid-wicket.
Tossed up, on off. Blocked out.
Loopy ball, on the pads. Nudged to square leg for a brace.
Full and on off, pushed to mid on.
Short of a length, around off. Brooks sits back in his crease and defends it cautiously.
Good-length delivery, around off. Brooks covers the line and blocks it onto the deck.
Back of a length, around off. Brooks defends it off the back foot.
Wide! A short ball, well above the batter's head. Brooks ducks underneath and the umpire calls it wide for height.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Overton strikes and this is a much-needed breakthrough for England! Overton serves another short ball. This time it is angling down leg. Campbell swivels and tries to pull but he only manages a tickle on it and the ball goes through to the keeper. Ben Foakes moves to his right and makes no mistake. West Indies lose their first wicket. Shamarh Brooks is the new batsman in.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b Craig Overton

Short ball, on leg. Pulled to deep mid-wicket for a single.

Back of a length, around off. Campbell hangs back to defend it.

Good-length ball, outside off. John Campbell lets it through to the keeper.
Fuller in length, outside off. John Campbell miscues his drive to mid off.
Full and on middle. John Campbell keeps it out.
FOUR! CRUNCHED! Back of a length, outside off. John Campbell stays back and punches it through covers for a boundary.
A tad short, outside off. Brathwaite cuts it towards point. Not in the gap though.
Flatter and quicker, on off. Brathwaite blocks if off the back foot.
Full ball, outside off. Brathwaite defends it off the front foot.
A quicker ball, on middle. Brathwaite keeps it out.
Tossed up, on off. Blocked out.
Full and on leg. Clipped to mid-wicket.
Short of a length, on middle. John Campbell hangs back and blocks it out. A maiden over from Woakes.
Fuller in length, outside off. John Campbell lets it sail through to the keeper.

On a length and way outside off. Campbell does not bother playing at that one.
Back of a length, angling across the batter. John Campbell lets it through to the keeper.

A bit quicker and going on with the arm from off. Kraigg Brathwaite stays back and blocks it to the leg side.
Flatter and quicker, around middle. Kraigg Brathwaite keeps it out.

Tossed up, around middle. Kraigg Brathwaite keeps it out off the front foot.
Floated, full and outside off. John Campbell skips down the track and pushes it to the off side for a single.
Flatter ball, around off. John Campbell rocks back and keeps it out.
On a length, around middle. Kraigg Brathwaite stays back and tucks it to the leg side.
Good-length delivery, around off. Kraigg Brathwaite looks to block but it takes the outside edge and the ball rolls away through the slip cordon for a couple of runs.
Fuller in length, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite prods and tucks it to mid-wicket.

Good-length ball, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite stays back and turns it to mid-wicket.
FOUR! PUNCHED! Back of a length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite stays back and slaps it through the backward point region to bag a boundary. Poor start from Woakes!
Chris Woakes to steam in from the other end.
Floated, on a length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite taps it to the off side and takes a single. 50 up for West Indies!
Flatter and quicker, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite nudges it to mid-wicket.
Flatter ball, on a length, around middle. John Campbell stays back and eases it to long on for one run.
Flatter ball, outside off. John Campbell rocks back and tries to keep it out but it goes off the underedge towards the first slip fielder.
FOUR! Innovative and also courageous from John Campbell! Full and outside off. Campbell kneels and reverse-sweeps it through point for a boundary.
Tossed up, outside off. John Campbell prods and defends it to the off side.

We are back for the middle session! The players stride out to the middle. Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell jog out as well to resume their innings. Jack Leach will start the session with the ball. Let's go...
... Day 2, Session 2 ...

Right then! England will be looking to make amends in the second session as their bowlers have been pretty wayward in the first one. West Indies will look to pile on more runs and keep the English bowlers at bay. Do join us for the second session which begins at 10.20 pm IST (4.50 pm GMT).

Earlier in the first session, it was England who crossed the 300-run mark in Tests for the first time in 13 innings and if not for Jonny Bairstow, they would have crumbled way before that. The tourists added just 43 runs on Day 2 before getting bowled out and they would have certainly liked a few more on the board. West Indies were excellent with the ball and it was the pace duo of Alzarri Joseph and Jayden Seales who picked two wickets apiece and made sure that England do not run away with the score.

A session that belongs to West Indies! Their openers had a tricky passage of play to see off just before the Lunch break and they have done extremely well to go unscathed into the break. The pair of Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell has come out with some positive intent and the English bowlers weren't upto the mark with the new cherry. Yes, a bit early to say this, but they did miss the experience of James Anderson and Stuart Broad with the new ball as all the bowlers lacked control in this passage of play.
Back of a length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite pushes it to mid on. Both the openers have weathered the storm nicely in this morning session. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 2!
Good-length ball bowled on the pads, Brathwaite tucks it round the corner to deep square leg where Leach has to cover some ground while stopping a boundary. Two taken!
FOUR! Short of a length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite hops and rides the bounce. He deliberately cuts it over the gully fielder and bags a boundary.
On a length,outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite steers it to deep backward point for a brace.
Length ball, angling in, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite is beaten by the bounce and gets struck near the box as he tries to work it on the leg side.
Bangs a short ball, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite sits under it.
Quicker delivery, on off. John Campbell defends it off the back foot. First maiden over of this innings.
Full and outside off, John Campbell smothers it to the off side.
Full and outside off. John Campbell keeps it out.
Tossed up, on middle, turning in. John Campbell defends it back to the bowler.
Floats it up, on middle, turning in. John Campbell gets struck on the thigh pad. The bal lobs towards short leg and they appeal for a catch but the umpire says no.
Loopy ball, outside off. John Campbell steps out and nudges it on the leg side.
Time for some spin as Jack Leach comes into the attack now. Can he get the breakthrough for England just at the stroke of Lunch?
Length ball, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite defends it towards covers.
Short and on middle and leg. Kraigg Brathwaite hops and tucks it to leg gully.
Full and spraying on the pads, flicked through mid-wicket for a run.
Bangs a bouncer, on middle. John Campbell ducks underneath. Good pace from Wood and a well-directed bouncer as well.
Short of a length, on off. Pulled nicely but straight to mid-wicket.
On a good length, on off. John Campbell blocks it out.
Full ball, on middle and leg. Kraigg Brathwaite nudges it to mid-wicket. This is West Indies' highest score after 7 overs in Test cricket since 2014.

FOUR! Well clipped! Full and on the pads, Kraigg Brathwaite clips it through mid-wicket. The ball races away into the vacant deep mid-wicket area and into the fence. Both the openers are playing nicely and with positive intent.
On a length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite keeps it out to the off side.
On off, blocked out.
FOUR! Sweetly timed! Fuller in length, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite presents the full face of the bat and drives it past the bowler to long off for a glorious boundary.
Nice and full, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite digs it out.
Change of ends for Craig Overton.
Once again it's full and going down leg. John Campbell misses his flick and the ball gets carried through to the keeper.
Full and angling down on leg, John Campbell misses his flick and gets hit on the pads. A stifled appeal for an lbw but that was clearly going down leg.
Length ball, on off. John Campbell is solid in his defence.
Fuller in length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite leans onto it and drives it through covers for a run.
On a length, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite taps it to point once again.
Length ball, outside off, at 139 clicks. Kraigg Brathwaite guides it to point.
Mark Wood comes into the attack. He replaces Craig Overton.
Back of a length, outside off. John Campbell punches it off the back foot through covers for a brace.
Full and angling across, left alone by Campbell.

Three taken! Short of a length, on off. An awkward defensive stroke from Kraigg Brathwaite. He just works it softly towards mid off but the ball still manages to go near the fence. The mid off fielder cuts it off. Three runs are taken!
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Kraigg Brathwaite shoulders arms to that.
Short of a length, on middle. Blocked out.
FOUR! Easy pickings! A loosener from Woakes, on the pads. Kraigg Brathwaite just tickles it down to fine leg and the ball races away to the fence.
Short of a length, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite hops and taps it to the off side.
On a length, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite blocks it to the off side.
John Campbell works this length ball behind square on the leg side for a single.
On a length, around off. John Campbell looks to defend. The ball goes off the outside edge towards gully. Doesn't get carried as it was played with soft hands.
Good-length ball, outside off, nipping away. John Campbell leaves it untouched.
On a length, on off. John Campbell just about keeps it out.
Length ball, on off. John Campbell pushes it to cover for a quick single. This is a good start by West Indies. Not allowing the pressure to come onto them.
Touch fuller, on middle, nipping in. John Campbell keeps it out off the front foot.
On a length, outside off. Left alone.
FOUR! Woakes goes full this time, on middle. John Campbell flicks it uppishly to deep mid-wicket for another boundary.
NO BALL! Good-length ball, outside off, swinging in. John Campbell with another defensive shot but the ball goes past the outside edge. Chris Woakes will have to reload as he has overstepped.
FOUR! First boundary of the Windies' innings! Short of a length, on middle. John Campbell gets on top of the bounce and pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a boundary.
That's a ripper! Good-length ball, closer to the off pole, angling across. John Campbell is forced to offer a shot. He tries to defend but the ball zips past the outside edge.
John Campbell is off the mark! Good-length ball, on off. Pushed to point for a quick single.
On a length, on off. Campbell defends it back to the bowler.
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. John Campbell leaves it alone.
Length ball, outside off, shaping away. John Campbell lets it sail through.

Craig Overton to bowl from the other end.
Good-length ball, outside off, shaping away. Kraigg Brathwaite makes a leave.

Woakes goes fuller this time, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite does well to block it out. A loud appreciation to Woakes from the slip cordon.
Shorter in length, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite defends it from the crease without any trouble.
Back of a length again, with a hint of away swing this time. Kraigg Brathwaite pushes it to the off side.
Woakes starts with a back-of-a-length ball, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite stands on his toes and defends it under his eyes.

We are all set for the final innings of this Test match! England players are out there in the huddle and they disperse now to take their respective positions. Kraigg Brathwaite and John Campbell are the openers for West Indies. Mark Wood is not on the field and he will not take any further part in this Test match. Chris Woakes to start with the ball for England. Kraigg Brathwaite will be on strike. Here we go...
... FOURTH INNINGS …

England have declared! Quite a bold decision this and West Indies now need 286 runs to win this game. England, on the other hand, have close to 70 overs to bowled out Windies and it will be quite an interesting passage of play before Lunch now. England came with an intent this morning and despite losing wickets kept scoring runs at the brisk interval and added 132 runs in their tally. The skipper. Joe Root got to his century and other chipped in with handy cameos. Windies bowlers were decent tough and got wickets at regular intervals. However, it remains to be seen now how their batting group reacts to this total. The match is poised quite nicely now and we are in for some thrilling action as both teams will be eager to get those crucial WTC points on the board. Stay tuned for the final innings of this Test match!
FOUR! Short delivery this time and it provides a boundary! A short delivery on middle. Bairstow pulls it fine towards long leg for a boundary.

Drinks! This has been an entertaining morning. Five wickets and plenty of runs scored as well. So things are getting quite interesting here and it remains to be seen how much more England score before they declare or get bowled out here. An interesting passage of play coming up. Chris Woakes is the next man in.

Ben Foakes is the next man in.

Stokes dances down the track and looks to go big downtown. However, he miscues it. The ball goes in the air towards long off and Shamarh Brooks there runs slightly forward and takes an easy catch.
Commentary.Howout: c Shamarh Brooks b Kemar Roach

Jonny Bairstow is the next man in.

OUT! KNOCKED HIM OVER! So Root departs now while trying to up the ante. Credit should also go to Alzarri Joseph, he has been very proactive with his bowling today. He sees Root getting across here and serves this very full on middle and leg. Root misses and the ball shatters the stumps. So Windies are chipping in with wickets and with lead now 246 batters will continue to keep going here. End of another supern knock by the English skipper, truly deserves all the applauds.

FOUR! Second new ball is available now but Windies have not taken it and Stokes starts the over with a boundary! A low full toss, on off. Stokes makes room and plays it inside-out overs covers for a boundary.
This is full and down the leg side. Root looks to clip it away but misses.
A slower length delivery, on off. Stokes works it towards the leg side for a quick single.
A short delivery on middle this time. Root pulls uppishly this time but short of the fine leg fielder for a single.
A length delivery, on off. Stokes tries to heave it away but gets the inside half of his blade to fine leg for a single.
Full delivery on middle. Root tucks it towards backward square leg for a single. A bit of mix-up there between the fielders but extra run not taken.
This one is slower on off from 'round the wicket. Stokes works it towards mid on for a single.
300 up for England and lead is now 236! A length delivery, around off. Stokes pushes it towards deep cover for a single.
Back of a length, around off. Stokes pushes it towards point.

He has surely given a good boost to this English innings.

Slower in the air and around leg again. Dan Lawrence makes room and defends it.
Slightly shorter on middle this time. Root goes back and works it towards deep mid-wicket for a single.
Continues with the same leg stump line. Root sweeps fine towards long leg for a couple.

FOUR BYES! This time the ball beats everyone! This is full and down the leg side. Root tries to sweep it but misses. Joshua Da Silva behind the stumps misses it too and the ball races away towards the fence.
A fuller delivery on leg stump. Root looks to sweep it but misses and the ball hits his pads.
A full delivery, outside off. Root drives it to deep point for a single.

A length delivery and wider outside off. Dan Lawrence gets across and hits it to long on for a single.

A length delivery on middle and leg. Root looks to reverse-sccoop it but gets the inside edge onto his body for a single towards the leg side. There is a stifled appeal but nothing more.
A full delivery, outside off. Dan Lawrence gets across and goes for a helicopter shot. The ball goes towards mid on pocket for a single.
Another delivery on leg stump. Dan Lawrence sweeps it to fine leg for another single.
Fuller delivery on middle and leg. This time Root sweeps it to fine leg for a single.
Down the leg side. Root looks to sweep but does not make any contact.
Flatter on leg this time. Dan Lawrence looks to sweep again but misses. The ball hits his pads and a leg bye is take towards square leg.
Fuller and tossed up down the leg side. Dan Lawrence looks to sweep it but misses.
FOUR! Veerasammy Permaul is greeted with a boundary! A flatter delivery on leg. Dan Lawrence reverse-sweeps it through backward point region for a boundary. Fifty partnership up.
Time for some spin. Veerasammy Permaul comes on to bowl now.
A length delivery, outside off and this one nips back in. Root looks to drive but gets beaten off the inside edge of his blade.
WIDE! A length delivery and a tad too wide outside off. Root goes chasing for it but misses.
A length delivery, on off. Dan Lawrence makes room and lifts it towards long off. The ball falls short of the fielder there and a single is taken.
A length delivery, outside off. Dan Lawrence gets across and looks to work it towards the leg side. He gets the leading edge towards the off side.
A length delivery, around off. Dan Lawrence looks to heave it away across the line but gets the inside edge onto his pads.

Century for Root! What a player this man is! It doesn’t matter whether he bats at number 4 or number 3, he continues to shine with the bat. This one is full and outside off. Root squeezes it to deep point for a single. He will look to step on the gas now!
A length delivery, on off. Root drives it to covers this time.

Drinks! Exactly what this game needed to spice things up. England have lost a wicket this morning but they are looking quite positive and are moving towards a score where they can declare and have a crack at Windies batting unit. The lead in now 205 and it remains to be seem how much more England feel they need to make a match of this. Windies have been decent in the first our but they need to tighten up now to restrict England here.
Back of a length, around off. Dan Lawrence works it towards the leg side.
FOUR! So runs are flowing now for England! Back of a length, on middle. Dan Lawrence makes room and slams it over extra-cover for a boundary.
Back of a length, on middle. Dan Lawrence works it towards mid-wicket.
Back of a length, on leg. Dan Lawrence makes room and mistimes his cut shot towards the off side.
Back of a length, on middle and leg. Root works it right of square leg for another single.
The lead is now 200! A length delivery, on middle. Dan Lawrence gets across and works it towards fine leg for a single.
Jayden Seales is back into the attack now.
A length delivery, on off. Root drives it back to the bowler.
A length delivery, around off. Dan Lawrence makes room and throws his bat at that. The ball goes towards the third man region for a single.
Slightly fuller on off this time. Root pushes it towards deep cover for a single.
A length delivery, on off. Root pushes it towards covers.
FOUR BYES! A wayward delivery this! A full toss down the leg side. Root looks to flick it but misses. Joshua Da Silva dives to his left to stop it but fails and the ball races away towards the fence.
Overpitched on off. Root drives it to deep extra-cover and gets a couple.
Back of a length, on middle. Dan Lawrence skips down the track and heaves it towards mid-wicket.
A length delivery on middle. Dan Lawrence looks to work it towards the leg side but gets a leading edge towards the off side.
SIX! Ohh...a maximum now! So England are going for it! A length delivery on middle.  Dan Lawrence makes room and tonks it over long off for a maximum.
Goes fuller this time on off. Dan Lawrence drives it to covers.
On a length, on off. Dan Lawrence blocks it towards the off side.
This one is full and down the leg side. Dan Lawrence skips down the track and looks to flick it but misses.
A length delivery, on off. Root pushes it towards the off side.
A length ball, outside off. Dan Lawrence cuts it to deep cover for a single.
WIDE! This is full and outside off. Dan Lawrence looks to get a bat on it but misses.
NO BALL! Very full and down the leg side. Dan Lawrence walks across again and looks to flick it but misses. Alzarri Joseph has overstepped there.
A length delivery, outside off again. Root cuts it without much timing towards backward point for a single.
Full and wider outside off. Root goes chasing for it but gets beaten.
This is short and outside off. Dan Lawrence cuts it to deep extra-cover and take three runs.
Dan Lawrence walks across towards the off side. Alzarri Joseph serves this wider outside off. Dan Lawrence looks to get a bat on it but misses.
Alzarri Joseph is back into the attack.
Excellent running again! A length delivery on middle end leg. Dan Lawrence makes room and pushes it towards mid on for a quick single.
A slower fuller delivery, on middle. Root nudges it towards fine leg for a single.
A fuller delivery, on leg. Dan Lawrence works it towards mid-wicket for a single. Holder is not happy with the fielder there.
This is fuller on middle. Root flicks it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Back of a length, on off. Dan Lawrence pushes it towards the off side and takes a quick single this time.
FOUR! Ohh..some intent from Dan Lawrence! A length delivery, around off. Dan Lawrence skips down the track and gives himself some room. He then slams it over extra-cover for a boundary.
A length delivery, on middle. Dan Lawrence works it towards mid-wicket and gets a single.
Provides the width again, outside off. Root pushes it towards covers for a single.
Another couple of runs! A length delivery, outside off. Root square drives it to deep point and comes back for the second run. He is into the 90s now.
Ohh...very full on middle this time. Root digs it out towards mid-wicket.
A length delivery, outside off and slower in pace at 110 kph. Root steers it toward deep backward point for a couple.
This is full on middle. Root leans forward and drives it to mid on.
Back of a length, on middle. Root works it towards fine leg for a single.
A slower length delivery, outside off. Root takes a step or two forward and defends it towards the off side.
This time drifting on the pads. Dan Lawrence works it towards fine leg for a single.
A good-length delivery, on off. Dan Lawrence defends it towards the off side.
Dan Lawrence is the next man in.

OUT! BOWLED! What a delivery by Jason Holder! He takes the pitch out of the equation this time and nails a perfect yorker! The ball shatters the off pole and a wicket for Windies early in the day.

Starts with a full delivery, on off. Zak Crawley drives it to mid off.
So as expected, Jason Holder replaces Nkrumah Bonner.
A fullish delivery, on off. Root drives it to covers this time. Tidy over to start by Roach.
A length delivery, around off. Root defends it towards the point fielder this time.
Another fullish delivery, on off. Root is well forward again and pushes it towards the off side.
A full delivery, on off. Root drives it to covers this time.

Direct hit and Zak Crawley would have been back to the dressiong room! A full delivery on middle. Zak Crawley drives it to mid on and sets off for a quick single. The fielder there collects the ball and has a shy at the bowler's end but misses. A single in the end.

We are all set to begin on Day 5! West Indies players are out there in the middle and Zak Crawley and Joe Root also walk out to the middle now to resume their innings. Nkrumah Bonner will also resume his over which was interrupted by rain on Day 4. Here we go...

The pitch has been pretty unresponsive for the bowlers while the batters have also struggled to score quickly due to the slow nature of the pitch. The conditions are expected to be more or less the same on the final day and Windies will need a special bowling effort in the first session of the day to garner any hopes of winning this Test. England, on the other hand, need to step on the gas and would be looking to add at least 100 runs to their kitty before they can think of declaring and having a crack at the Windies' batting lineup. The rain played spoilsport in the final session of Day 4 and let us hope that it stays away on this final day. An interesting first session coming up. Stay tuned for further updates.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 5 of this first Test between West Indies and England. We are into the final day of this Test match but one must say that the game has not progressed at a pace where we can say that we will surely get a winner at the end of this Test match. At this point in time, a draw seems the most likely result but cricket is a funny game and we have seen Test matches take some exciting turns on the final day. England had a productive Day 4 as they wrapped up the Windies innings in the first over of the day itself and then Zak Crawley and Root made sure that they lost only one wicket throughout the day and eventually ended with a lead of 153 runs. England look like the more liklier of the two teams coming into the final day to push for a win and let's see how things pan out on the final day of this Test match.
...Day 5, Session 1...

Right then! Day 4 was interrupted by rain and we hope that it stays away on the final day of this Test match. We are in for an exciting finish to this Test as all three results are still possible, however, draw seems to be the most likely of them. The final day will begin half an hour early i.e. at 7 pm IST (1.30 pm GMT). But as usual, the build-up will begin well in advance. Do join us for the same. Cheers!

Zak Crawley is up for a quick chat. He says that he enjoyed batting out in the middle and also credits Joe Root for the way he batted alongside him. Mentions that they will give themselves a chance in the morning on Day 5 and says, they still have a chance of winning this Test.

West Indies toiled hard. They managed to pick just one wicket, that too very early on and after that, there was nothing much for them. Although, the pitch is dead and not supportive, their bowlers were a bit widish and did not create enough sustaining pressure while Veerasammy Permaul was taken to cleaners. West Indies will be grateful that rain came in late and the tired minds can push on the final day of this Test match. England, on the other hand, have already lost some overs today and it is very dubious for a result but anything can happen in a Test match.

Just a quick glance at how the day went. England bossed the day thoroughly. They did well to take the last Windies wicket quickly and started their proceedings with intent. However, Alex Lees fell in the process but since then the visitors bossed each and every session. Zak Crawley and Joe Root combined to build a partnership of 193 runs. Crawley has notched up his second Test century while the skipper alongside, is also looking for a triple-digit score. England came into the final session with much more aggression as they scored more boundaries and did not allow the spinners to ease up. They were on a good course but the rain interruptions came unplanned in between.

Slower through the air, well outside off. Joe Root pushes it to the off side and takes a single.

Flatter ball, on middle and leg. Zak Crawley nudges it behind square on the leg side for a single.

Kemar Roach to burst in now.

Bye! Back of a length, down leg. Zak Crawley misses his pull shot and the keeper fails to grab the ball cleanly. The batters collect a bye. 200 comes up for England!
Seales comes 'round the wicket and serves a short ball, around leg. Joe Root swivels and pulls it towards fine leg for a single.

On middle, hit to mid-wicket.

Around off. Root plays it to point for one more.

On off, Blocked out.

Touch fuller and on off. Root mistimes his push back to the bowler.

FOUR! England have just put a shift to the gears! Tossed up, on middle. Root gets low and sweeps it to square leg for a boundary.

West Indies though would be disappointed as nothing has gone their way so far on Day 4, except the wicket of Alex Lees. Their bowlers have toiled hard but to no avail. The pacers have been a tad inconsistent in the middle session and their spinner, Veerasammy Permaul has looked completely out of sorts so far in this innings. The hosts now need wickets in quick succession if they are to restrict the scoring. Do join us for the last session of Day 4 which begins at 1.00 am IST (7.30 pm GMT, previous day).

Another session that has been dominated by England! They have stretched the lead to 82, without losing a wicket in the middle session and the partnership between Root and Crawley is now 122! Both of them got to their fifties in this session and they are looking well-set to get a big one here. England are making sure that they get to a position from where they can't lose this Test.

England are in the lead now and West Indies need to make sure that they make some early inroads post Lunch, as this partnership can take the game away for them. We are in for another exciting session and the middle session will begin at 10.20 pm IST (4.50 pm GMT). Do join us then.

Earlier in the session, it was Jack Leach who wrapped things up quickly for England as he took the last Windies wicket in the very first over of Day 4, and then it was onto the English batters to see off the new ball and provide their team a good start. The debutant, Alex Lees once again perished early but his partner, Zak Crawley along with Joe Root batted really well and they have ensured that they do not lose any more wickets heading into the Lunch break. West Indies started well with the ball, as their veteran, Kemar Roach got rid of Alex Lees and he was the pick of the bowler yet again for the hosts. Veerasammy Permaul was introduced just before the break but he leaked some runs as Crawley didn't allow him to settle in.

End of a riveting first session on Day 4! West Indies' pacers continued to ask some serious questions with the new ball but the pair of Root and Crawley have weathered the storm well so far and have made sure that they do not repeat the mistakes that they did in the first innings. The tourists now lead by 8 runs and would be reasonably happy going into the Lunch break, having cut down the deficit at the cost of just one wicket.

Right then! That is all we have from the fifth and final day of the first Test match between West Indies and England and the match has ended in a DRAW, leaving the three-match series wide open. The second Test match will be played in Barbados from the 16th of March. That match will begin at 7.30 pm IST (2 pm GMT) but as usual, the build up will begin much sooner. Do join us then. Till then, take care and goodbye!

Kraigg Brathwaite, the captain of West Indies says that it was a hard-fought draw and adds that the effort has been good from the team. He mentions that they were good with the new ball and they need to do better when the ball gets old and put pressure on the opposition team throughout the innings. He applauds Nkrumah Bonner for his effort and says that he is a special player. He mentions that there will be more for the pacers in Barbados. He says that there are some areas they can improve especially in the middle overs and they need to tighten up in that aspect.

England skipper, Joe Root says that he is really proud of the team and the character they showed after being put on the back foot right in the first hour itself. He then goes on to hail the performances of Jonny Bairstow and Jack Leach and also mentions Crawley's effort on the last day. On being asked about losing Wood, he says that yes with the ball reversing a bit he would have been useful but no one can stop an in-game injury. Also adds that Crawley is now one of the senior batters in the side and after last year, it has been brilliant from him to pick himself up and put on the performance. Ends by saying that they are looking forward to Barbados now.

Nkrumah Bonner is the PLAYER OF THE MATCH! He says that he likes to bat on this venue. He says that they wanted to win the game but are happy with the draw. He mentions that as a Test batter he needs to bat long and he did exactly that. He mentions that they showed a lot of character in this Test and says that they have a lot of positives from this game.
Presentation time...

West Indies bowlers were treated to a barrage of strokes from the English batters early in the day but did well to keep picking up wickets at regular intervals. The visitors did set the Windies a target but the home side never looked likely to force the issue and have a go at winning the match. It was a sensible move though and after a decent start from skipper Kraigg Brathwaite, John Campbell and Jermaine Blackwood played a couple of really bad shots to put their team in trouble. It was then a familiar partnership between Nkrumah Bonner and Jason Holder and just like the first innings, the pair just stood firm and frustrated the opposition bowlers. Bonner especially just gave nothing away and played almost 500 balls in the whole Test match. The Windies will be happy with a draw here but things could have been different and they could have probably taken a couple of risks in the match.

England pressed the issue hard on the final day but it was always going to be a daunting task to pick up 10 wickets on a surface that had barely anything in it for the bowlers in a bit over two sessions. Root was aggressive and did take a risk when he declared just before Lunch. The English bowlers found it difficult to get the opening breakthrough but once they got Brathwaite, they had an opening and one wicket became two in a flash. It was slow going then but on the stroke of Tea, Jack Leach got his second wicket of the innings. The visitors came out for the final session believing and a wicket early in the final session made things interesting. They probed and probed with Ben Stokes bending his back to the fullest as well but couldn't pick up any more wickets, succumbing to the dead pitch. Joe Root will be a bit disappointed here as one could see the look of desperation on his face to win this Test match.

Finally, the two sides decide to call it a day! Joe Root goes up to the Windies batters and shakes hands and the match has turned out to be as we expected. A match that had everything, a few stellar batting performances, a bit of rain delay, a docile pitch and an exciting final day, well barring the last session. But it was the pitch that won and neither side could force the issue enough to get a result in their favour.

Windies were going well for the most part of the session but they lost three wickets in the later half of the session and that will be disappointing for the Caribbean boys. The skipper, Braithwaite and Campbell put together a solid opening stand and despite both of them departing in quick succession, the Windies have a lot of batting in their belly to salvage a draw here. The pitch no doubt is not helping the bowlers as much as a Day 5 pitch should but neither is it easy for the batters to score quickly. So, a Windies win is out of the equation and they would just look to bat the final session of this session with resilience and authority to take the confidence into the next game. However, this game has a knack of dishing out surprises every now and then, and let’s see what is in store for us in the final session of this Test match. The last session starts at 12.30 am IST (7.00 pm GMT, the previous day). Stay tuned.

So, a wicket for England just at the stroke of Tea and that has ensured that the doors are still open for England. However, still 7 wickets to go and it is still quite a daunting task on this slow and low pitch. Unless, of course, West Indies decide to shoot on their own feet and self implode here. It was a hard toil for English bowlers with the x-factor of Mark Wood missing but they kept putting in efforts and eventually the man for the crisis, Ben Stokes broke the opening stand. Leach was the pick of the bowlers and managed to take two wickets to keep his team in the game but England needed at least one more wicket in this afternoon session to take more optimism and hope with them coming into the Tea break.

OUT! TAKEN! You could hear Zak Crawley saying 'that's a nice shot' on the previous delivery and now he takes a really sharp catch to make this match even more interesting. Beautifully bowled by Jack Leach yet again. Flighted, on off with a bit of drift in. The ball pitches, grips and turns away enough. Shamarh Brooks presses forward to defend but gets the outside edge and Crawley gets low quickly to grab the ball before it hits the ground at first slip. England get another wicket and that too on the cusp of the Tea interval.
Commentary.Howout: c Zak Crawley b Jack Leach

...Day 5, Session 2...

Windies bowlers were put under pressure right from the start in the morning session but they reacted quite well and bowled some clever lines and lengths to restrict the scoring rate. They managed to take five wickets in this session and they will be overall pleased with their effort this morning. However, the real task is yet to be completed and their batters need to step up in the post-Lunch session. The pitch is still good to bat on and they will fancy playing out two sessions on this final day but a victory cannot be ruled out and it remains to be seen how they approach the afternoon session. The post-Lunch session starts at 10.10 pm IST (4.40 pm GMT). Stay tuned.

What an engrossing session of Test cricket this has been! England came out with great intent and stepped on the gas putting the Windies bowlers under pressure with a brisk scoring rate. They lost wickets on the way though but that did not derail their spirit and they kept going for their shots. Zak Crawley was the first man to depart but Dan Lawrence came in and started going from ball one and that provided impetus to the innings and that allowed skipper, Root to declare earlier than most people aniticipated. The reset button that was hit before this game for the English Test cricket has surely made them a bolder and more enterprising unit. It is upto their bowlers now to produce a special effort and script a famous victory here.

So, the Windies openers have safely negotiated this tricky phase of 24 balls! We have a match on our hands now folks! England have 67 overs to bowl out West Indies and register a win here while the men from the Caribbean need 282 runs more to script a famous victory here. All three results are possible here and if the action continues to be as edgy as it has been in the first session we are in for a treat on this final day of the first Test match.
